WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:02.940 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:02.940 --> 00:00:05.390 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.390 --> 00:00:12.560 align:middle line:90%


00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:15.650 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK, today is our
second and probably last day

00:00:15.650 --> 00:00:19.100 align:middle line:84%
of homogeneous dynamics
and projection theory.

00:00:19.100 --> 00:00:22.670 align:middle line:84%
Let's remember where
we are, and then we're

00:00:22.670 --> 00:00:25.040 align:middle line:84%
going to try to
use the things we

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:29.240 align:middle line:84%
learned about last time to
say something about dynamics.

00:00:29.240 --> 00:00:36.360 align:middle line:84%
So we'll have a Lie group
G, which so far is SL2R.

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:43.790 align:middle line:84%
And we have a discrete subgroup,
which so far has been SL2Z.

00:00:43.790 --> 00:00:45.745 align:middle line:84%
And we're interested
in G mod gamma.

00:00:45.745 --> 00:00:48.470 align:middle line:90%


00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:57.510 align:middle line:84%
We'll have a metric m, which is
a right invariant metric on G.

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:03.520 align:middle line:84%
And then it leads to a
metric that I'll also

00:01:03.520 --> 00:01:05.115 align:middle line:90%
call m on G mod gamma.

00:01:05.115 --> 00:01:07.690 align:middle line:90%


00:01:07.690 --> 00:01:16.930 align:middle line:84%
So now G also has a left
action on G mod gamma.

00:01:16.930 --> 00:01:20.680 align:middle line:84%
And this left action does
not preserve the metric,

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:22.790 align:middle line:84%
because the metric is
not left invariant.

00:01:22.790 --> 00:01:25.490 align:middle line:84%
So this left action
distorts the metric.

00:01:25.490 --> 00:01:27.410 align:middle line:84%
And we started to
study that last time,

00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:29.500 align:middle line:84%
and it's going to
continue to be crucial

00:01:29.500 --> 00:01:31.060 align:middle line:90%
how it distorts the metric.

00:01:31.060 --> 00:01:33.555 align:middle line:90%
But it preserves the volume.

00:01:33.555 --> 00:01:43.660 align:middle line:90%


00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:51.280 align:middle line:84%
Now, inside of this group,
we have the unitary group.

00:01:51.280 --> 00:01:52.755 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, the unipotent group.

00:01:52.755 --> 00:01:57.370 align:middle line:90%


00:01:57.370 --> 00:02:01.030 align:middle line:90%
Let's say UT is 1 1 t.

00:02:01.030 --> 00:02:04.855 align:middle line:84%
And our goal is to understand
how the unipotent orbits in G

00:02:04.855 --> 00:02:06.340 align:middle line:90%
mod gamma look.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:13.430 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to study
u dot x in G mod gamma.

00:02:13.430 --> 00:02:14.880 align:middle line:90%
So x is in G mod gamma.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:19.390 align:middle line:90%


00:02:19.390 --> 00:02:26.380 align:middle line:84%
And there's an old theorem of
Hedlund from the '30s, which is

00:02:26.380 --> 00:02:28.840 align:middle line:84%
the kind of thing about this
orbit that we're interested

00:02:28.840 --> 00:02:36.850 align:middle line:84%
in that u dot x is
either periodic or dense.

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:38.680 align:middle line:84%
We won't exactly
prove that, but we'll

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:40.680 align:middle line:84%
prove some things that
are a little bit related.

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:44.578 align:middle line:90%


00:02:44.578 --> 00:02:47.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, the unipotent
group is special.

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:49.363 align:middle line:84%
And the one way of
getting our hands

00:02:49.363 --> 00:02:51.280 align:middle line:84%
on something special
about it is to see how it

00:02:51.280 --> 00:02:53.450 align:middle line:90%
relates to diagonal matrices.

00:02:53.450 --> 00:02:57.330 align:middle line:84%
So let's say this a
sub r is that matrix,

00:02:57.330 --> 00:02:59.590 align:middle line:90%
that diagonal matrix in SL2R.

00:02:59.590 --> 00:03:06.510 align:middle line:84%
And then acute observation is
that a sub r UT a sub r inverse

00:03:06.510 --> 00:03:08.657 align:middle line:90%
is u e to the 2rt.

00:03:08.657 --> 00:03:12.510 align:middle line:90%


00:03:12.510 --> 00:03:14.928 align:middle line:84%
It's just a computation
with matrices.

00:03:14.928 --> 00:03:16.470 align:middle line:84%
I've done it a couple
of times, and I

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:19.123 align:middle line:84%
start to-- anyway, doing
it in front of you,

00:03:19.123 --> 00:03:20.290 align:middle line:90%
I think, is not very useful.

00:03:20.290 --> 00:03:23.430 align:middle line:84%
But if you are interested in
this, if you do it yourself,

00:03:23.430 --> 00:03:24.785 align:middle line:90%
it starts to make sense.

00:03:24.785 --> 00:03:27.561 align:middle line:90%


00:03:27.561 --> 00:03:39.030 align:middle line:84%
So now let's say that u0t of x,
that means the set of ut of x t

00:03:39.030 --> 00:03:40.590 align:middle line:90%
is in 0t.

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:43.790 align:middle line:84%
So if capital T is large, this
is a big piece of an orbit.

00:03:43.790 --> 00:03:45.790 align:middle line:84%
And that's more or less
what we'd like to study.

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:47.950 align:middle line:84%
What is the shape of a
big piece of the orbit?

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:55.830 align:middle line:84%
And this observation
tells us that u0t of x

00:03:55.830 --> 00:04:05.490 align:middle line:90%
is ar u01 ar inverse of x.

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:09.600 align:middle line:84%
And this is helpful, because
this u01 is much less

00:04:09.600 --> 00:04:11.400 align:middle line:90%
intimidating than u0t.

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:14.940 align:middle line:84%
So this here is just a
little piece of the orbit.

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.970 align:middle line:84%
And so to understand
a big orbit,

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:21.329 align:middle line:84%
we have to understand how this
a sub r acts on a little orbit.

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:23.830 align:middle line:90%


00:04:23.830 --> 00:04:27.150 align:middle line:84%
And another simple
observation is that ar

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:32.170 align:middle line:90%
is like a little r to the j.

00:04:32.170 --> 00:04:37.440 align:middle line:84%
So if big R is big J times
little r, then we have this.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:47.020 align:middle line:84%
Oh, in this equation, by the way
e to the big r is t So this ar,

00:04:47.020 --> 00:04:51.100 align:middle line:84%
we can think of it as a
little r applied many times.

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:53.870 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, it makes
sense that we could just

00:04:53.870 --> 00:05:02.395 align:middle line:84%
try to understand how a little
r acts on unipotent orbits.

00:05:02.395 --> 00:05:11.474 align:middle line:90%


00:05:11.474 --> 00:05:14.150 align:middle line:84%
So we made a picture of
this at the end of class

00:05:14.150 --> 00:05:17.820 align:middle line:84%
last time with models
and props and everything.

00:05:17.820 --> 00:05:23.330 align:middle line:84%
And this picture
is the main tool

00:05:23.330 --> 00:05:26.263 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to think
about for homogeneous dynamics.

00:05:26.263 --> 00:05:27.930 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to draw
this picture again,

00:05:27.930 --> 00:05:29.780 align:middle line:84%
and then we're going
to talk about why

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:31.165 align:middle line:90%
it is the way we drew it.

00:05:31.165 --> 00:05:34.112 align:middle line:90%


00:05:34.112 --> 00:05:39.170 align:middle line:84%
So over here, a
shape that I'll draw

00:05:39.170 --> 00:05:40.710 align:middle line:90%
as being kind of a cylinder.

00:05:40.710 --> 00:05:44.150 align:middle line:84%
And this is a
fundamental domain.

00:05:44.150 --> 00:05:46.760 align:middle line:84%
So this is either the whole
fundamental domain or maybe

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:51.260 align:middle line:90%
a tube in f.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:58.520 align:middle line:84%
So f is sitting in the group G,
and it's a fundamental domain

00:05:58.520 --> 00:06:01.110 align:middle line:90%
for G mod gamma.

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:04.060 align:middle line:90%


00:06:04.060 --> 00:06:11.430 align:middle line:84%
And so this length scale is 1,
and this length scale is also 1.

00:06:11.430 --> 00:06:13.160 align:middle line:84%
Or we could also make
it smaller if we'd

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:16.050 align:middle line:90%
like to have a thinner tube.

00:06:16.050 --> 00:06:18.350 align:middle line:84%
And now inside of
this tube are a bunch

00:06:18.350 --> 00:06:21.595 align:middle line:84%
of pieces of unipotent orbit
that I'll draw like this.

00:06:21.595 --> 00:06:32.630 align:middle line:90%


00:06:32.630 --> 00:06:37.220 align:middle line:84%
So each of those is a
piece of unipotent orbit.

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:40.930 align:middle line:84%
Here is t equals 0 and
here is t equals 1.

00:06:40.930 --> 00:06:44.010 align:middle line:90%


00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:47.330 align:middle line:84%
And now I understand what is
going to happen to this picture

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:50.290 align:middle line:90%
when we apply a sub r.

00:06:50.290 --> 00:06:57.620 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to apply,
I guess strictly speaking,

00:06:57.620 --> 00:06:59.120 align:middle line:84%
we're going to apply
it on the left.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:02.140 align:middle line:84%
We're going to multiply
by a sub r on the left.

00:07:02.140 --> 00:07:05.170 align:middle line:90%
So what's going to happen?

00:07:05.170 --> 00:07:08.110 align:middle line:84%
So first of all,
the unipotent orbits

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:11.350 align:middle line:90%
are going to stretch that way.

00:07:11.350 --> 00:07:14.922 align:middle line:84%
And then second of
all, so if you just

00:07:14.922 --> 00:07:16.630 align:middle line:84%
think about what
happens to the cylinder,

00:07:16.630 --> 00:07:18.730 align:middle line:84%
there's going to be a direction
where it stretches, there's

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:20.690 align:middle line:84%
going to be a direction
that compresses,

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:23.140 align:middle line:84%
and there's going to be a
direction that stays the same.

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:25.270 align:middle line:84%
That would be true
at every point.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:29.350 align:middle line:84%
But what's important is that
the direction that compresses

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:32.750 align:middle line:84%
is kind of not the same
everywhere in this picture.

00:07:32.750 --> 00:07:34.390 align:middle line:84%
And so to illustrate
that, I'm going

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:38.170 align:middle line:84%
to draw what happens at a
couple of different heights.

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:52.110 align:middle line:90%
So at t equals 1, I have this.

00:07:52.110 --> 00:07:55.000 align:middle line:84%
And there will be some
direction that compresses.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.090 align:middle line:90%
Maybe it's that direction.

00:07:57.090 --> 00:08:00.930 align:middle line:84%
And so when we
apply lar inverse,

00:08:00.930 --> 00:08:05.340 align:middle line:84%
this disk is going to
be squished vertically.

00:08:05.340 --> 00:08:07.380 align:middle line:84%
And when it's
squished vertically,

00:08:07.380 --> 00:08:10.790 align:middle line:84%
then we'll have a triangle
that looks sort of like so.

00:08:10.790 --> 00:08:13.830 align:middle line:90%


00:08:13.830 --> 00:08:19.050 align:middle line:84%
And also at t equals 0,
we have the same disk

00:08:19.050 --> 00:08:20.615 align:middle line:90%
with the same triangle in it.

00:08:20.615 --> 00:08:25.620 align:middle line:90%


00:08:25.620 --> 00:08:29.320 align:middle line:84%
But there's a compression
direction, which is different.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:32.250 align:middle line:84%
So maybe down here
it's this direction.

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:37.559 align:middle line:84%
So when we apply
la sub r inverse,

00:08:37.559 --> 00:08:42.240 align:middle line:84%
then we will get a pancake
and get squished this way.

00:08:42.240 --> 00:08:46.600 align:middle line:84%
And that will affect
these points differently.

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:50.520 align:middle line:84%
After squishing, the green
point and the orange point

00:08:50.520 --> 00:08:51.980 align:middle line:90%
will be quite close together.

00:08:51.980 --> 00:08:54.670 align:middle line:90%


00:08:54.670 --> 00:08:57.620 align:middle line:84%
So that's the picture that
we ended with last time.

00:08:57.620 --> 00:09:00.960 align:middle line:90%


00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:06.780 align:middle line:84%
And what is important
here, key point,

00:09:06.780 --> 00:09:20.340 align:middle line:84%
is that the compression
direction is twisting relative

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:24.200 align:middle line:90%
to the unipotent orbits.

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:29.730 align:middle line:90%


00:09:29.730 --> 00:09:32.110 align:middle line:84%
Meaning that if
at a given height,

00:09:32.110 --> 00:09:35.590 align:middle line:84%
two unipotent orbits are being
compressed towards each other,

00:09:35.590 --> 00:09:38.945 align:middle line:84%
then at most other
heights, they won't be.

00:09:38.945 --> 00:09:43.290 align:middle line:90%


00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:47.210 align:middle line:84%
So this is where we
left off last time.

00:09:47.210 --> 00:09:51.220 align:middle line:84%
Are there questions or
comments about this picture?

00:09:51.220 --> 00:10:01.460 align:middle line:90%


00:10:01.460 --> 00:10:02.840 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:02.840 --> 00:10:05.400 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So in the
picture you had last week,

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:07.250 align:middle line:84%
these [INAUDIBLE]
things are all kind of

00:10:07.250 --> 00:10:09.410 align:middle line:84%
stretched out and compressed
and then mapped back

00:10:09.410 --> 00:10:11.300 align:middle line:90%
onto the fundamental domain.

00:10:11.300 --> 00:10:15.020 align:middle line:84%
But if they've been
twisted around,

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:17.210 align:middle line:84%
are they kind of
mapped back onto f

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:20.430 align:middle line:84%
without twisting in some way to
make it all perfectly line up?

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:22.880 align:middle line:84%
Or is there some other
twisting that happens again

00:10:22.880 --> 00:10:25.880 align:middle line:90%
as they get back into f?

00:10:25.880 --> 00:10:27.570 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Yeah, yeah.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:29.330 align:middle line:90%
OK, that's a good question.

00:10:29.330 --> 00:10:33.440 align:middle line:84%
So the question is about
how this gets mapped back

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:34.920 align:middle line:90%
into the fundamental domain.

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:36.295 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to draw that also.

00:10:36.295 --> 00:10:39.680 align:middle line:90%


00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:45.980 align:middle line:84%
So here's our
fundamental domain.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:49.650 align:middle line:84%
First we apply this
map just in our group,

00:10:49.650 --> 00:10:55.843 align:middle line:84%
and we get something
which is tall and flat.

00:10:55.843 --> 00:10:59.900 align:middle line:90%


00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:02.810 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps, it is
twisted a little bit

00:11:02.810 --> 00:11:04.330 align:middle line:90%
between the bottom and the top.

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:08.570 align:middle line:90%


00:11:08.570 --> 00:11:13.980 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, then that is going to
get mapped back into our domain.

00:11:13.980 --> 00:11:17.700 align:middle line:84%
So pi is the projection
from G to G mod gamma.

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:21.600 align:middle line:84%
And G mod gamma will identify
with our fundamental domain.

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:23.510 align:middle line:84%
So this thing is
going to get back

00:11:23.510 --> 00:11:24.900 align:middle line:90%
into the fundamental domain.

00:11:24.900 --> 00:11:27.710 align:middle line:90%
What does that look like?

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:32.810 align:middle line:84%
So the fundamental domain
is kind of a unit cube.

00:11:32.810 --> 00:11:35.550 align:middle line:84%
But this thing is way
taller than a unit cube.

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:38.350 align:middle line:84%
So imagine cutting
it into pieces

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:41.980 align:middle line:90%
whose height is only around 1.

00:11:41.980 --> 00:11:44.420 align:middle line:90%
And this was only ever around 1.

00:11:44.420 --> 00:11:46.810 align:middle line:84%
So each of those pieces
now is small enough

00:11:46.810 --> 00:11:49.360 align:middle line:84%
to fit in the
fundamental domain.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:55.660 align:middle line:84%
And let me call it piece
one, piece two, piece three,

00:11:55.660 --> 00:11:58.490 align:middle line:90%
and piece four.

00:11:58.490 --> 00:12:01.270 align:middle line:84%
Now, those are
going to fold back

00:12:01.270 --> 00:12:04.360 align:middle line:90%
into the fundamental domain.

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:07.030 align:middle line:84%
And at least
roughly, I think it's

00:12:07.030 --> 00:12:08.700 align:middle line:90%
good to imagine it like this.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:11.290 align:middle line:90%


00:12:11.290 --> 00:12:15.280 align:middle line:84%
So each one of these
guys corresponds

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.440 align:middle line:90%
to one of those guys.

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:20.360 align:middle line:90%
But they are not in order.

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:22.760 align:middle line:84%
So it's not like
they go 1, 2, 3, 4.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:29.200 align:middle line:90%
They're in some order, 1, 2, 3.

00:12:29.200 --> 00:12:34.442 align:middle line:84%
So I don't know much
about this order.

00:12:34.442 --> 00:12:36.525 align:middle line:84%
I personally don't know
anything about this order.

00:12:36.525 --> 00:12:47.800 align:middle line:90%


00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.960 align:middle line:84%
OK, so now I think
the question was,

00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:53.650 align:middle line:84%
how would this picture
look if this thing were

00:12:53.650 --> 00:12:56.740 align:middle line:90%
twisted a little bit?

00:12:56.740 --> 00:13:00.160 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, when we say
that this thing is twisted

00:13:00.160 --> 00:13:04.450 align:middle line:84%
a little bit, it's something
like a change of 90 degrees

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:07.250 align:middle line:84%
or 180 degrees between
the bottom and the top.

00:13:07.250 --> 00:13:09.823 align:middle line:84%
And there are many steps
between the bottom and the top.

00:13:09.823 --> 00:13:11.990 align:middle line:84%
So that means if you just
look at one of these guys,

00:13:11.990 --> 00:13:15.260 align:middle line:84%
you don't notice or barely
notice any twisting.

00:13:15.260 --> 00:13:19.108 align:middle line:84%
This thing is basically
a planar slab.

00:13:19.108 --> 00:13:21.650 align:middle line:84%
And then these planar slabs are
at slightly different angles.

00:13:21.650 --> 00:13:25.958 align:middle line:84%
But this map pi, it
doesn't exactly preserve--

00:13:25.958 --> 00:13:28.000 align:middle line:84%
I mean, those angles aren't
exactly well defined,

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.140 align:middle line:84%
because this is
not living in R3.

00:13:30.140 --> 00:13:33.070 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually not
clear exactly what

00:13:33.070 --> 00:13:35.680 align:middle line:84%
we mean when we say that
this slab and this slab,

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:39.540 align:middle line:84%
are they parallel or are they
twisted compared to each other?

00:13:39.540 --> 00:13:43.434 align:middle line:84%
Anyway, when they
get mapped back in,

00:13:43.434 --> 00:13:46.660 align:middle line:84%
I think that imagining
this is reasonable.

00:13:46.660 --> 00:13:56.710 align:middle line:90%


00:13:56.710 --> 00:13:58.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, that raises a
bit of a question,

00:13:58.410 --> 00:14:02.340 align:middle line:84%
coming back to this
picture that we were

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:03.780 align:middle line:90%
trying to digest last time.

00:14:03.780 --> 00:14:07.170 align:middle line:84%
What exactly do we mean when
we say that the compression

00:14:07.170 --> 00:14:09.300 align:middle line:90%
angle is twisting?

00:14:09.300 --> 00:14:12.725 align:middle line:84%
Because the compression angle
here lives at one height.

00:14:12.725 --> 00:14:14.850 align:middle line:84%
It lives over here, and
the compression angle there

00:14:14.850 --> 00:14:15.640 align:middle line:90%
lives over there.

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And how do we compare
an angle over here

00:14:17.910 --> 00:14:22.810 align:middle line:84%
with an angle over here
given that this is not R3,

00:14:22.810 --> 00:14:25.380 align:middle line:84%
this is living in
a curved thing?

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:29.110 align:middle line:84%
So I actually rethought
how to state it,

00:14:29.110 --> 00:14:30.780 align:middle line:84%
and I added some
words that I don't

00:14:30.780 --> 00:14:33.440 align:middle line:90%
think I mentioned last time.

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:35.820 align:middle line:84%
I think when we talk
about this twisting,

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:38.090 align:middle line:84%
we need to include
these words relative

00:14:38.090 --> 00:14:39.370 align:middle line:90%
to the unipotent orbits.

00:14:39.370 --> 00:14:42.000 align:middle line:90%


00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.860 align:middle line:84%
So let me try to make a more
precise statement about what

00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:47.780 align:middle line:84%
this twisting means,
and then we'll

00:14:47.780 --> 00:14:50.360 align:middle line:84%
see how we can do some
computations in the Lie group

00:14:50.360 --> 00:14:52.450 align:middle line:84%
with matrices and
see that it happens.

00:14:52.450 --> 00:15:16.700 align:middle line:90%


00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:17.315 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:15:17.315 --> 00:15:21.140 align:middle line:90%


00:15:21.140 --> 00:15:21.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:15:21.870 --> 00:15:28.855 align:middle line:84%
So precise statement
about what is twisting.

00:15:28.855 --> 00:15:33.410 align:middle line:90%


00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:34.360 align:middle line:90%
What is twisting.

00:15:34.360 --> 00:15:38.000 align:middle line:90%


00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.570 align:middle line:84%
So suppose I have a
piece of unipotent orbit

00:15:41.570 --> 00:15:43.610 align:middle line:90%
in my fundamental domain.

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:45.750 align:middle line:90%
It starts at G0.

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:47.790 align:middle line:84%
That's over there,
some group element,

00:15:47.790 --> 00:15:50.060 align:middle line:90%
and our fundamental domain.

00:15:50.060 --> 00:15:54.170 align:middle line:84%
And then over here
I have UT of G0.

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:56.450 align:middle line:90%
And t goes, say, from 0 to 1.

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:59.130 align:middle line:90%


00:15:59.130 --> 00:16:02.480 align:middle line:84%
Now, at each point
here, there's going

00:16:02.480 --> 00:16:07.790 align:middle line:84%
to be a vector that
compresses when I perform ar.

00:16:07.790 --> 00:16:12.050 align:middle line:90%
So let's say v compression of t.

00:16:12.050 --> 00:16:18.500 align:middle line:84%
This is a vector, and
this is the direction

00:16:18.500 --> 00:16:30.565 align:middle line:84%
that compresses when we
apply a left ar inverse.

00:16:30.565 --> 00:16:33.640 align:middle line:90%


00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:35.390 align:middle line:90%
So it's a vector.

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:42.040 align:middle line:84%
It lives in the tangent space
of our group at the given point.

00:16:42.040 --> 00:16:51.580 align:middle line:84%
And it's the smallest
singular vector

00:16:51.580 --> 00:16:54.090 align:middle line:90%
for the derivative of this map.

00:16:54.090 --> 00:16:56.950 align:middle line:90%


00:16:56.950 --> 00:17:01.030 align:middle line:84%
So that's what we mean by
the compression direction.

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:05.619 align:middle line:84%
Now, what does it mean relative
to the unipotent orbits?

00:17:05.619 --> 00:17:12.280 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that over here I
have another unipotent orbit.

00:17:12.280 --> 00:17:15.330 align:middle line:84%
And this is like a
nearby unipotent orbit.

00:17:15.330 --> 00:17:24.130 align:middle line:90%


00:17:24.130 --> 00:17:31.970 align:middle line:84%
So this might be G0
plus epsilon times v0.

00:17:31.970 --> 00:17:34.870 align:middle line:84%
Epsilon times v0
is a little vector

00:17:34.870 --> 00:17:38.830 align:middle line:84%
that goes between these
starting points of these two

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:40.780 align:middle line:90%
nearby unipotent orbits.

00:17:40.780 --> 00:17:49.510 align:middle line:84%
And up here, or maybe here,
is UT of G0 plus epsilon v0.

00:17:49.510 --> 00:17:53.860 align:middle line:84%
And here there's a vector
that goes between them,

00:17:53.860 --> 00:18:00.220 align:middle line:84%
I guess, epsilon
times v orbit of t.

00:18:00.220 --> 00:18:05.710 align:middle line:84%
So v orbit of t is going in the
direction from the red orbit

00:18:05.710 --> 00:18:06.675 align:middle line:90%
to the orange orbit.

00:18:06.675 --> 00:18:10.180 align:middle line:90%


00:18:10.180 --> 00:18:19.090 align:middle line:84%
So the thing that is
twisting is v compression

00:18:19.090 --> 00:18:22.940 align:middle line:84%
of t relative to v
orbit of t is twisting.

00:18:22.940 --> 00:18:25.990 align:middle line:84%
The angle between those
two vectors is changing.

00:18:25.990 --> 00:18:30.160 align:middle line:84%
That's the precise statement
of what is twisting.

00:18:30.160 --> 00:18:32.980 align:middle line:84%
And we can check
what it's happening

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:34.940 align:middle line:90%
by computing these two vectors.

00:18:34.940 --> 00:18:35.570 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:18:35.570 --> 00:18:36.445 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:36.445 --> 00:19:12.333 align:middle line:90%


00:19:12.333 --> 00:19:13.750 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So
the question has

00:19:13.750 --> 00:19:16.360 align:middle line:84%
to do with keeping track of
things, given that they live

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.950 align:middle line:90%
in different tangent spaces.

00:19:18.950 --> 00:19:22.720 align:middle line:84%
So the compression
direction is a vector

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:27.760 align:middle line:84%
in the tangent space at the
given point along the orbit.

00:19:27.760 --> 00:19:28.640 align:middle line:90%
Is that OK so far?

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:32.910 align:middle line:90%


00:19:32.910 --> 00:19:33.630 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:35.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:19:35.790 --> 00:19:36.730 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:19:36.730 --> 00:19:40.680 align:middle line:84%
But then the
comment is if I have

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:43.120 align:middle line:84%
a family of vectors
in one vector space,

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:44.910 align:middle line:84%
then I can say that
they're twisted.

00:19:44.910 --> 00:19:47.130 align:middle line:84%
But here I have a
family of vectors

00:19:47.130 --> 00:19:49.270 align:middle line:90%
in a family of vector spaces.

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:54.300 align:middle line:84%
And so it's not so clear what
it means that they're twisting.

00:19:54.300 --> 00:19:56.550 align:middle line:84%
One way to do it is to
pick a reference vector

00:19:56.550 --> 00:19:57.850 align:middle line:90%
to compare them with.

00:19:57.850 --> 00:20:03.570 align:middle line:84%
And so that's the job of this
v orbit vector, which goes

00:20:03.570 --> 00:20:06.180 align:middle line:90%
from the red vector to this--

00:20:06.180 --> 00:20:08.670 align:middle line:84%
from the red orbit
to this orange orbit.

00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:13.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's like a
reference vector.

00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:15.250 align:middle line:90%
And then we'll see that--

00:20:15.250 --> 00:20:19.420 align:middle line:84%
so at each t, there's an orbit
vector and a compression vector,

00:20:19.420 --> 00:20:23.455 align:middle line:84%
and the angle between
them is changing.

00:20:23.455 --> 00:20:31.910 align:middle line:90%


00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:36.620 align:middle line:84%
So there was a question last
class that basically was like,

00:20:36.620 --> 00:20:39.510 align:middle line:84%
how are we sure that this is
happening in this picture?

00:20:39.510 --> 00:20:46.010 align:middle line:84%
And the one way to be sure is
to compute these two vectors

00:20:46.010 --> 00:20:48.420 align:middle line:84%
and see that they're
not the same.

00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:55.140 align:middle line:90%


00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:56.110 align:middle line:90%
So let's compute them.

00:20:56.110 --> 00:21:00.980 align:middle line:90%


00:21:00.980 --> 00:21:03.540 align:middle line:84%
Actually, one of them we
can compute over here.

00:21:03.540 --> 00:21:08.930 align:middle line:90%


00:21:08.930 --> 00:21:12.780 align:middle line:90%
So UT is a matrix.

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:17.190 align:middle line:84%
So we can just
multiply this through.

00:21:17.190 --> 00:21:22.970 align:middle line:84%
This is UT G0 plus
epsilon UT of v0.

00:21:22.970 --> 00:21:27.910 align:middle line:84%
And if we compare sides,
we see that v orbit of t

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:36.010 align:middle line:84%
is u sub t of v.
Now, let's figure out

00:21:36.010 --> 00:21:37.755 align:middle line:90%
what v compression of t is.

00:21:37.755 --> 00:22:18.970 align:middle line:90%


00:22:18.970 --> 00:22:24.820 align:middle line:84%
So say we have some
G0 and we're going

00:22:24.820 --> 00:22:28.610 align:middle line:84%
to apply the left
action of ar inverse.

00:22:28.610 --> 00:22:35.860 align:middle line:84%
And that will move
us to a sub r of G0.

00:22:35.860 --> 00:22:38.470 align:middle line:84%
And we want to understand
how this map is

00:22:38.470 --> 00:22:40.520 align:middle line:90%
distorting the geometry of G0.

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:42.230 align:middle line:90%
The geometry near G0.

00:22:42.230 --> 00:22:43.780 align:middle line:84%
And in particular,
figure out which

00:22:43.780 --> 00:22:45.530 align:middle line:90%
direction is being compressed.

00:22:45.530 --> 00:22:49.552 align:middle line:90%


00:22:49.552 --> 00:22:52.480 align:middle line:84%
So I think the best
way I could figure out

00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:57.760 align:middle line:84%
to understand this is to put
it in a picture connecting

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:00.460 align:middle line:84%
this thing that I don't
understand yet to some maps that

00:23:00.460 --> 00:23:02.860 align:middle line:90%
are easier to understand.

00:23:02.860 --> 00:23:04.610 align:middle line:90%
So here's the identity.

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:07.750 align:middle line:84%
And from here to here, I could
apply a right multiplication

00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:09.070 align:middle line:90%
by G0.

00:23:09.070 --> 00:23:11.860 align:middle line:84%
And right multiplication is
much easier to understand,

00:23:11.860 --> 00:23:13.750 align:middle line:90%
because that's an isometry.

00:23:13.750 --> 00:23:17.670 align:middle line:84%
And the identity also is kind
of nicer than other matrices.

00:23:17.670 --> 00:23:22.140 align:middle line:84%
And then I'm going to
go back to the identity.

00:23:22.140 --> 00:23:26.040 align:middle line:84%
So this is right
multiplication by ar g0

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.340 align:middle line:84%
all inverse, which
is also an isometry.

00:23:29.340 --> 00:23:31.440 align:middle line:84%
So if you put this
all together, I'm

00:23:31.440 --> 00:23:34.530 align:middle line:84%
going to have a map from the
tangent space of the identity

00:23:34.530 --> 00:23:37.200 align:middle line:90%
to itself.

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:40.463 align:middle line:84%
And that map is
an isometry times

00:23:40.463 --> 00:23:41.880 align:middle line:84%
the map I want to
understand times

00:23:41.880 --> 00:23:45.060 align:middle line:84%
an isometry so that all
of the metric distortion

00:23:45.060 --> 00:23:46.475 align:middle line:90%
is going to come from here.

00:23:46.475 --> 00:23:49.626 align:middle line:90%


00:23:49.626 --> 00:23:53.350 align:middle line:84%
Now, this map is not
so hard to understand.

00:23:53.350 --> 00:23:55.560 align:middle line:90%
So if I apply--

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:56.350 align:middle line:90%
what am I doing?

00:23:56.350 --> 00:23:56.850 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:23:56.850 --> 00:23:59.430 align:middle line:90%
I start with some matrix h.

00:23:59.430 --> 00:24:01.480 align:middle line:90%
Right multiply by G0.

00:24:01.480 --> 00:24:04.210 align:middle line:90%
Then I left multiply by ar.

00:24:04.210 --> 00:24:09.270 align:middle line:84%
Then I right multiply
by the inverse of ar G0.

00:24:09.270 --> 00:24:10.690 align:middle line:90%
What do I get?

00:24:10.690 --> 00:24:13.050 align:middle line:90%
Well, I have h.

00:24:13.050 --> 00:24:15.810 align:middle line:90%
I multiply on the right by G0.

00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:18.930 align:middle line:84%
Now I multiply on
the left by ar.

00:24:18.930 --> 00:24:20.600 align:middle line:90%
I multiply on the right by this.

00:24:20.600 --> 00:24:23.700 align:middle line:90%


00:24:23.700 --> 00:24:27.240 align:middle line:84%
When I invert this,
I switch those.

00:24:27.240 --> 00:24:29.075 align:middle line:84%
I get a G0 inverse
and they cancel.

00:24:29.075 --> 00:24:32.910 align:middle line:90%


00:24:32.910 --> 00:24:38.800 align:middle line:84%
So this operation is none
other than conjugating by ar.

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.070 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
conjugation by arh.

00:24:41.070 --> 00:24:43.660 align:middle line:90%


00:24:43.660 --> 00:24:48.310 align:middle line:84%
So conjugation by ar is a map
from our new group to itself,

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:50.440 align:middle line:84%
takes the identity
to the identity.

00:24:50.440 --> 00:24:53.820 align:middle line:84%
And therefore, this map,
or really its derivative,

00:24:53.820 --> 00:24:58.500 align:middle line:84%
takes the tangent space
of the identity to itself.

00:24:58.500 --> 00:24:59.670 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:01.750 align:middle line:90%
And now you can write this down.

00:25:01.750 --> 00:25:04.740 align:middle line:90%
This ar is an explicit matrix.

00:25:04.740 --> 00:25:08.310 align:middle line:84%
A Tangent vector here
is a matrix ABCD.

00:25:08.310 --> 00:25:14.510 align:middle line:84%
So this is just
ABCD goes to DCAR

00:25:14.510 --> 00:25:24.397 align:middle line:84%
of this is er minus
r, ABCD e or minus r.

00:25:24.397 --> 00:25:25.980 align:middle line:84%
So this is a thing
you can write down.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:27.090 align:middle line:90%
It's not that scary.

00:25:27.090 --> 00:25:30.440 align:middle line:84%
And we worked out last
time what it does.

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:35.070 align:middle line:84%
So recall from last time
that we have-- first of all,

00:25:35.070 --> 00:25:39.770 align:middle line:84%
we have an orthonormal
basis of Te of G,

00:25:39.770 --> 00:25:43.650 align:middle line:84%
which are-- there's a
basis vector n, 0, 1, 0, 0.

00:25:43.650 --> 00:25:45.523 align:middle line:84%
Last time I called
this u, but there

00:25:45.523 --> 00:25:46.940 align:middle line:84%
were so many u's
on the blackboard

00:25:46.940 --> 00:25:48.750 align:middle line:84%
that I was worried it
was not a great idea,

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:53.630 align:middle line:84%
so I'm going to call it n. n for
nilpotent, which is also true.

00:25:53.630 --> 00:25:57.090 align:middle line:84%
There's n tilde,
which is 0, 1, 0, 0.

00:25:57.090 --> 00:26:02.060 align:middle line:84%
And there's a diagonal
guy, which looks like this.

00:26:02.060 --> 00:26:02.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:09.890 align:middle line:84%
So What we figured out is
that the conjugation makes

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:16.700 align:middle line:84%
n way bigger, it makes
n tilde way smaller,

00:26:16.700 --> 00:26:18.925 align:middle line:84%
and it leaves the
diagonal fixed.

00:26:18.925 --> 00:26:29.390 align:middle line:90%


00:26:29.390 --> 00:26:30.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:30.380 --> 00:26:34.740 align:middle line:84%
So, if I start at the identity
and I go all the way around,

00:26:34.740 --> 00:26:37.820 align:middle line:84%
I'm doing this
conjugation, and n tilde

00:26:37.820 --> 00:26:40.696 align:middle line:84%
is the vector that's
going to get compressed.

00:26:40.696 --> 00:26:43.370 align:middle line:90%


00:26:43.370 --> 00:26:46.310 align:middle line:84%
But now, if I want to
know what vector over here

00:26:46.310 --> 00:26:49.790 align:middle line:84%
is going to get compressed,
Well, I start with n tilde,

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:51.060 align:middle line:90%
I map it over here.

00:26:51.060 --> 00:26:53.820 align:middle line:84%
It hasn't gotten any shorter
yet because this is an isometry.

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:56.850 align:middle line:84%
That's the vector that's going
to be compressed in this step.

00:26:56.850 --> 00:26:59.540 align:middle line:90%


00:26:59.540 --> 00:27:01.016 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:27:01.016 --> 00:27:08.800 align:middle line:84%
So, it's the right
action by g0 of n tilde.

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:21.280 align:middle line:84%
This is the singular vector of
dLar inverse with singular value

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:22.740 align:middle line:90%
e to the minus 2r.

00:27:22.740 --> 00:27:26.710 align:middle line:90%


00:27:26.710 --> 00:27:29.600 align:middle line:84%
OK, so that's basically
the answer to our question.

00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:37.150 align:middle line:84%
So the compression
vector at T, that's

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:40.540 align:middle line:84%
r at-- so now I'm not
necessarily at the point g0,

00:27:40.540 --> 00:27:49.090 align:middle line:84%
but I'm at the point ut g0, so
it's right by ut g0 of n tilde.

00:27:49.090 --> 00:27:52.800 align:middle line:90%
So that's n tilde ut g.

00:27:52.800 --> 00:28:01.780 align:middle line:90%


00:28:01.780 --> 00:28:02.640 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:02.640 --> 00:28:07.230 align:middle line:84%
So now, if you compare how these
two things are changing with T,

00:28:07.230 --> 00:28:10.620 align:middle line:84%
you see, it is not the same
because our group is not

00:28:10.620 --> 00:28:12.630 align:middle line:90%
commutative.

00:28:12.630 --> 00:28:15.610 align:middle line:84%
Because when you're
changing the orbit of T,

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:18.310 align:middle line:84%
you're multiplying
by ut on the left.

00:28:18.310 --> 00:28:21.310 align:middle line:84%
But when you're changing
the compression direction,

00:28:21.310 --> 00:28:25.440 align:middle line:84%
you're multiplying by ut
over here in the middle.

00:28:25.440 --> 00:28:26.950 align:middle line:84%
And it's a
non-commutative group,

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:29.420 align:middle line:84%
so those two operations are
not the same as each other.

00:28:29.420 --> 00:28:49.860 align:middle line:90%


00:28:49.860 --> 00:28:50.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:50.760 --> 00:28:54.000 align:middle line:84%
So I don't necessarily
think it will

00:28:54.000 --> 00:28:55.570 align:middle line:84%
be helpful to do
more computations,

00:28:55.570 --> 00:28:57.540 align:middle line:84%
but I did some at
home to be sure,

00:28:57.540 --> 00:29:03.250 align:middle line:84%
if you imagined that at time 0,
these two directions coincided,

00:29:03.250 --> 00:29:05.740 align:middle line:84%
and then you see what
happens as T changes,

00:29:05.740 --> 00:29:08.970 align:middle line:84%
you'll see that they
stop to coincide.

00:29:08.970 --> 00:29:09.488 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:29:09.488 --> 00:29:12.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So it can be the inner
product of the vectors, does

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:16.840 align:middle line:84%
it make sense as an operation to
compare the angles in the space?

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:18.340 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH:
Yeah, that's right.

00:29:18.340 --> 00:29:22.230 align:middle line:84%
So these are vectors in
a Riemannian manifold,

00:29:22.230 --> 00:29:24.940 align:middle line:84%
and so they have a
well-defined angle,

00:29:24.940 --> 00:29:27.400 align:middle line:84%
and we can compute it by
taking inner products.

00:29:27.400 --> 00:29:31.860 align:middle line:90%
And then-- correct.

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:46.020 align:middle line:84%
So I guess we could say that the
cosine of the angle between v

00:29:46.020 --> 00:29:56.420 align:middle line:84%
of t and w of t would be v dot
w over norm of v norm of w.

00:29:56.420 --> 00:29:59.340 align:middle line:90%


00:29:59.340 --> 00:30:01.690 align:middle line:84%
I used to teach
this a lot in 1802.

00:30:01.690 --> 00:30:03.260 align:middle line:90%
I think that's right.

00:30:03.260 --> 00:30:07.400 align:middle line:84%
So we have formulas for v and
w, so we can compute this.

00:30:07.400 --> 00:30:10.130 align:middle line:84%
And it'll be a little
messy, but we'll

00:30:10.130 --> 00:30:15.290 align:middle line:84%
see that it is not
constant in T. OK.

00:30:15.290 --> 00:30:19.070 align:middle line:90%


00:30:19.070 --> 00:30:20.350 align:middle line:90%
Other questions or comments?

00:30:20.350 --> 00:30:28.370 align:middle line:90%


00:30:28.370 --> 00:30:29.130 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:32.010 align:middle line:84%
So the first big goal-- that was
the first chunk of the class.

00:30:32.010 --> 00:30:33.620 align:middle line:84%
The first big goal
of the class was

00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:38.660 align:middle line:84%
to check that this
picture happens.

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:40.850 align:middle line:84%
And then the second
part of the class, we

00:30:40.850 --> 00:30:43.760 align:middle line:84%
will discuss how
to use this picture

00:30:43.760 --> 00:30:48.090 align:middle line:84%
to figure out stuff about
along unipotent orbit.

00:30:48.090 --> 00:30:48.590 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:30:48.590 --> 00:30:50.065 align:middle line:90%
So let's switch gears.

00:30:50.065 --> 00:31:17.415 align:middle line:90%


00:31:17.415 --> 00:31:17.915 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:17.915 --> 00:31:30.320 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:30.840 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:30.840 --> 00:31:37.240 align:middle line:84%
So let's call this tracking
the spread of an order.

00:31:37.240 --> 00:31:43.370 align:middle line:90%


00:31:43.370 --> 00:31:44.250 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:31:44.250 --> 00:31:51.453 align:middle line:84%
So remember that we had
this, U0,T of x is aR U0,

00:31:51.453 --> 00:31:56.160 align:middle line:90%
1 aR inverse x.

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:58.986 align:middle line:90%
Let's call this guy x tilde.

00:31:58.986 --> 00:31:59.486 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:31:59.486 --> 00:32:02.748 align:middle line:90%


00:32:02.748 --> 00:32:06.260 align:middle line:84%
Now this-- there was a
discussion last time,

00:32:06.260 --> 00:32:11.350 align:middle line:84%
what happens if this
orbit here is periodic?

00:32:11.350 --> 00:32:14.290 align:middle line:84%
If this orbit here is periodic,
the special thing that happens

00:32:14.290 --> 00:32:17.900 align:middle line:84%
is that this point, x tilde,
will be deep in the cusp.

00:32:17.900 --> 00:32:20.482 align:middle line:84%
And the deep in the
cusp is a special case

00:32:20.482 --> 00:32:21.940 align:middle line:84%
because we were
imagining that this

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.940 align:middle line:84%
was a regular nice
orbit of length 1,

00:32:24.940 --> 00:32:28.150 align:middle line:84%
but if it's deep in the
cusp, it's different.

00:32:28.150 --> 00:32:31.830 align:middle line:84%
So, let's assume that x tilde
is not deep in the cusp.

00:32:31.830 --> 00:32:37.090 align:middle line:90%


00:32:37.090 --> 00:32:41.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's equivalent
to saying that Ux is not

00:32:41.500 --> 00:32:42.463 align:middle line:90%
close to periodic.

00:32:42.463 --> 00:32:47.350 align:middle line:90%


00:32:47.350 --> 00:32:48.330 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:32:48.330 --> 00:32:53.470 align:middle line:84%
And let's break up R as
capital J times little r.

00:32:53.470 --> 00:33:00.670 align:middle line:84%
And so then I'm going to say
that Uj is a little r to the j

00:33:00.670 --> 00:33:05.890 align:middle line:90%
of U0,1 of x tilde.

00:33:05.890 --> 00:33:06.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:33:06.790 --> 00:33:10.210 align:middle line:84%
And I want to track how
this thing is spreading out

00:33:10.210 --> 00:33:12.680 align:middle line:84%
through my homogeneous
space, GY gamma.

00:33:12.680 --> 00:33:17.020 align:middle line:84%
And we're going to track it by
noticing how many delta balls

00:33:17.020 --> 00:33:18.580 align:middle line:90%
it takes to cover it.

00:33:18.580 --> 00:33:25.720 align:middle line:84%
So recall that X delta is
the minimum number of delta

00:33:25.720 --> 00:33:32.740 align:middle line:90%
balls needed to cover X.

00:33:32.740 --> 00:33:36.196 align:middle line:84%
And so our goal is
going to be to estimate.

00:33:36.196 --> 00:33:38.890 align:middle line:90%


00:33:38.890 --> 00:33:46.935 align:middle line:84%
Uj delta in terms
of j, delta, and r.

00:33:46.935 --> 00:33:51.550 align:middle line:90%


00:33:51.550 --> 00:33:52.490 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:33:52.490 --> 00:33:56.940 align:middle line:84%
And for context,
for reference, we

00:33:56.940 --> 00:33:58.450 align:middle line:90%
have a three-dimensional space.

00:33:58.450 --> 00:33:59.935 align:middle line:84%
So for the whole
space, the number

00:33:59.935 --> 00:34:01.560 align:middle line:84%
of delta balls that
we need to cover it

00:34:01.560 --> 00:34:02.960 align:middle line:90%
is delta to the minus 3.

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:08.364 align:middle line:90%


00:34:08.364 --> 00:34:08.864 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:08.864 --> 00:34:12.570 align:middle line:90%


00:34:12.570 --> 00:34:14.400 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:18.510 align:middle line:84%
All right, so next
of all, our Uj

00:34:18.510 --> 00:34:21.522 align:middle line:84%
is like a bunch of
these unipotent orbits.

00:34:21.522 --> 00:34:28.050 align:middle line:90%


00:34:28.050 --> 00:34:29.489 align:middle line:90%
Looks like that.

00:34:29.489 --> 00:34:33.750 align:middle line:84%
And so you might
notice that it only

00:34:33.750 --> 00:34:36.610 align:middle line:84%
really matters what the top
cross-section looks like.

00:34:36.610 --> 00:34:38.980 align:middle line:84%
All the other
cross-sections are similar.

00:34:38.980 --> 00:34:41.880 align:middle line:84%
So let's take that
top part down.

00:34:41.880 --> 00:34:44.400 align:middle line:90%
Inside of there, we see this.

00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:46.840 align:middle line:90%
So let's call that Xj.

00:34:46.840 --> 00:34:55.190 align:middle line:84%
That's the top
cross-section of Uj.

00:34:55.190 --> 00:34:59.510 align:middle line:84%
And then it's not hard
to check that Uj delta is

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:03.560 align:middle line:84%
like delta inverse
times Xj delta.

00:35:03.560 --> 00:35:08.780 align:middle line:84%
I have to cut it into
slabs of thickness delta.

00:35:08.780 --> 00:35:11.120 align:middle line:84%
For each thickness, the
number of delta balls

00:35:11.120 --> 00:35:13.740 align:middle line:84%
that we need to cover
that slab is Xj delta,

00:35:13.740 --> 00:35:16.267 align:middle line:90%
and this is the number of slats.

00:35:16.267 --> 00:35:16.767 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:35:16.767 --> 00:35:23.390 align:middle line:84%
So basically, we want to track
how Xj delta depends on delta.

00:35:23.390 --> 00:35:26.740 align:middle line:90%
So, fully spread.

00:35:26.740 --> 00:35:29.840 align:middle line:90%


00:35:29.840 --> 00:35:32.990 align:middle line:90%
Or maybe I'll say very spread.

00:35:32.990 --> 00:35:39.020 align:middle line:84%
That means that Uj delta is
like delta to the minus 3,

00:35:39.020 --> 00:35:43.640 align:middle line:84%
and that would be like saying Xj
delta, so delta to the minus 2

00:35:43.640 --> 00:35:44.570 align:middle line:90%
at Xj.

00:35:44.570 --> 00:35:46.090 align:middle line:90%
Really fills a lot of the disc.

00:35:46.090 --> 00:35:50.612 align:middle line:90%


00:35:50.612 --> 00:35:57.320 align:middle line:84%
So now, how does this picture
help us to study Xj delta?

00:35:57.320 --> 00:36:17.690 align:middle line:90%


00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:20.470 align:middle line:90%
So using the key picture.

00:36:20.470 --> 00:36:24.710 align:middle line:90%


00:36:24.710 --> 00:36:25.325 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:36:25.325 --> 00:36:31.340 align:middle line:90%


00:36:31.340 --> 00:36:37.280 align:middle line:84%
So let me label these maps pi
1 and pi minus 0, and somewhere

00:36:37.280 --> 00:36:39.830 align:middle line:84%
in the middle we
would have pi t.

00:36:39.830 --> 00:36:45.030 align:middle line:84%
Pi t is what our map aR is
doing to the slice at height t.

00:36:45.030 --> 00:36:48.700 align:middle line:90%


00:36:48.700 --> 00:36:49.600 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:55.330 align:middle line:84%
Using the key
picture, have a lemma.

00:36:55.330 --> 00:37:02.440 align:middle line:84%
So if e to the
minus 2r is delta,

00:37:02.440 --> 00:37:16.980 align:middle line:84%
then Xj plus 1 delta is around a
sum over t of pi t of xj delta.

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:21.310 align:middle line:90%


00:37:21.310 --> 00:37:23.860 align:middle line:90%
And which t's do we sum over?

00:37:23.860 --> 00:37:29.510 align:middle line:84%
The t's are in delta Z,
and t goes from 0 to 1.

00:37:29.510 --> 00:37:36.430 align:middle line:90%


00:37:36.430 --> 00:37:39.490 align:middle line:84%
This is all-- we can also
write this as delta inverse

00:37:39.490 --> 00:37:45.100 align:middle line:84%
times the average
t between 0 and 1

00:37:45.100 --> 00:37:48.030 align:middle line:90%
of pi t height of Xj delta.

00:37:48.030 --> 00:37:52.480 align:middle line:90%


00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:54.765 align:middle line:90%
So, proof sketch.

00:37:54.765 --> 00:38:02.176 align:middle line:90%


00:38:02.176 --> 00:38:02.676 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:02.676 --> 00:38:06.224 align:middle line:90%


00:38:06.224 --> 00:38:08.660 align:middle line:84%
So here is our
fundamental domain.

00:38:08.660 --> 00:38:12.360 align:middle line:84%
Cut it into slices
of thickness delta.

00:38:12.360 --> 00:38:16.360 align:middle line:90%


00:38:16.360 --> 00:38:20.290 align:middle line:84%
So here is a slice at height
t with thickness delta.

00:38:20.290 --> 00:38:20.990 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:38:20.990 --> 00:38:27.756 align:middle line:84%
Now, when we apply Lar, we
stretch it up vertically.

00:38:27.756 --> 00:38:31.600 align:middle line:90%


00:38:31.600 --> 00:38:34.070 align:middle line:84%
And we compress it in
some other direction,

00:38:34.070 --> 00:38:36.070 align:middle line:90%
we get something like this.

00:38:36.070 --> 00:38:43.060 align:middle line:84%
And then we divide this into
pieces at different heights.

00:38:43.060 --> 00:38:50.340 align:middle line:84%
And let me color this
particular slab in red.

00:38:50.340 --> 00:38:55.620 align:middle line:84%
So that red one is
one of them over here.

00:38:55.620 --> 00:38:58.100 align:middle line:90%
So these are each of height 1.

00:38:58.100 --> 00:39:02.410 align:middle line:90%


00:39:02.410 --> 00:39:02.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:07.305 align:middle line:90%


00:39:07.305 --> 00:39:07.805 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:39:07.805 --> 00:39:13.620 align:middle line:90%


00:39:13.620 --> 00:39:15.400 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:20.250 align:middle line:84%
So, in this new picture, there
will be-- so in the old picture,

00:39:20.250 --> 00:39:25.865 align:middle line:84%
there were some unipotent orbits
that went through our slab.

00:39:25.865 --> 00:39:29.340 align:middle line:90%


00:39:29.340 --> 00:39:33.000 align:middle line:84%
So, X describes where
the unipotent orbits

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:35.040 align:middle line:90%
hit the top of our slab.

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:38.190 align:middle line:84%
And now, we apply this
map, and now there

00:39:38.190 --> 00:39:41.920 align:middle line:84%
will be some points over
here in the top of this slab.

00:39:41.920 --> 00:39:44.520 align:middle line:90%
And who will they be?

00:39:44.520 --> 00:39:51.645 align:middle line:84%
Those points over there
would be pi t of X.

00:39:51.645 --> 00:39:52.145 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:39:52.145 --> 00:39:55.260 align:middle line:84%
Now we want to cover
things with delta balls.

00:39:55.260 --> 00:40:00.690 align:middle line:84%
So this distance here is e to
the minus 2r, so that's delta.

00:40:00.690 --> 00:40:04.530 align:middle line:84%
So we want to know how
many delta balls does

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:09.180 align:middle line:90%
it take to cover that?

00:40:09.180 --> 00:40:14.460 align:middle line:84%
So, that number there is delta
covering number of pi t of Xj.

00:40:14.460 --> 00:40:20.334 align:middle line:90%


00:40:20.334 --> 00:40:23.430 align:middle line:84%
So over here, we
started with xj.

00:40:23.430 --> 00:40:28.260 align:middle line:84%
Now, what happens
when we apply pi?

00:40:28.260 --> 00:40:31.715 align:middle line:84%
Each of these slabs
gets folded back in.

00:40:31.715 --> 00:40:37.530 align:middle line:90%


00:40:37.530 --> 00:40:42.750 align:middle line:90%
And the red one went somewhere.

00:40:42.750 --> 00:40:45.505 align:middle line:84%
I don't really know where,
but maybe it went over here.

00:40:45.505 --> 00:40:49.490 align:middle line:90%


00:40:49.490 --> 00:40:53.300 align:middle line:84%
And here in the
top of it is pi t

00:40:53.300 --> 00:40:58.430 align:middle line:84%
of Xj and its
delta-covering number.

00:40:58.430 --> 00:41:06.170 align:middle line:84%
So the number of delta
balls in this strip, that

00:41:06.170 --> 00:41:09.530 align:middle line:90%
would be pi t of Xj.

00:41:09.530 --> 00:41:12.740 align:middle line:90%


00:41:12.740 --> 00:41:13.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:17.180 align:middle line:90%
And now, this thing--

00:41:17.180 --> 00:41:22.340 align:middle line:84%
these dots up here
are our Xj plus 1.

00:41:22.340 --> 00:41:25.500 align:middle line:84%
So the set of dots
on the top face.

00:41:25.500 --> 00:41:28.860 align:middle line:84%
And so how many delta balls
do we need to cover them?

00:41:28.860 --> 00:41:33.150 align:middle line:84%
Well, for these ones, we needed
pi t Xj delta-covering number,

00:41:33.150 --> 00:41:37.580 align:middle line:84%
and these other guys, those
corresponded to different slabs

00:41:37.580 --> 00:41:39.800 align:middle line:84%
here, so there are
different terms in this set.

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:56.862 align:middle line:90%


00:41:56.862 --> 00:41:57.362 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:41:57.362 --> 00:42:00.014 align:middle line:90%


00:42:00.014 --> 00:42:05.800 align:middle line:84%
So now, we can try to
use projection theory

00:42:05.800 --> 00:42:08.530 align:middle line:84%
to study this thing,
and it will tell us

00:42:08.530 --> 00:42:11.140 align:middle line:84%
how the covering
number Xj plus 1 delta

00:42:11.140 --> 00:42:34.871 align:middle line:84%
evolves as we increase
J. Any questions-- yeah.

00:42:34.871 --> 00:42:37.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Why do-- like,
we have delta balls start

00:42:37.840 --> 00:42:39.760 align:middle line:84%
to overlap when
j is large enough

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:42.680 align:middle line:84%
and the compression
is more than delta

00:42:42.680 --> 00:42:46.960 align:middle line:84%
because delta is the size
of one round of compression.

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:48.900 align:middle line:84%
If you do multiple,
why do they overlap?

00:42:48.900 --> 00:42:56.830 align:middle line:90%


00:42:56.830 --> 00:42:59.170 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: So I
think the question is,

00:42:59.170 --> 00:43:03.010 align:middle line:84%
suppose at the beginning
that there happened

00:43:03.010 --> 00:43:07.930 align:middle line:84%
to be two guys here in X
whose distance was less

00:43:07.930 --> 00:43:09.865 align:middle line:90%
than delta, which might happen.

00:43:09.865 --> 00:43:13.695 align:middle line:84%
And then, what would
happen to them?

00:43:13.695 --> 00:43:17.440 align:middle line:90%


00:43:17.440 --> 00:43:18.290 align:middle line:90%
Well--

00:43:18.290 --> 00:43:20.120 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Not that
they're less than delta.

00:43:20.120 --> 00:43:28.120 align:middle line:84%
If slightly more than delta, but
less than e to the minus 2r or e

00:43:28.120 --> 00:43:34.780 align:middle line:84%
to the 2r delta, so that in f,
they're in the same delta ball.

00:43:34.780 --> 00:43:38.910 align:middle line:84%
Then applying the
transformation, the [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.850 align:middle line:84%
or transformation method,
then they become [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:41.850 --> 00:43:42.790 align:middle line:90%
delta ball.

00:43:42.790 --> 00:43:45.502 align:middle line:90%


00:43:45.502 --> 00:43:47.460 align:middle line:84%
But before they're
not in-- before,

00:43:47.460 --> 00:43:49.170 align:middle line:84%
there were two separate delta
balls; after the transformation,

00:43:49.170 --> 00:43:50.473 align:middle line:90%
there's one delta ball.

00:43:50.473 --> 00:43:51.640 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right, right.

00:43:51.640 --> 00:43:54.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, so it could happen
that we have two guys--

00:43:54.780 --> 00:43:57.670 align:middle line:84%
like maybe these two guys
are pretty far apart,

00:43:57.670 --> 00:44:03.570 align:middle line:84%
but after we perform pi t,
they got squished together

00:44:03.570 --> 00:44:06.210 align:middle line:84%
and they're now in the
same delta ball over here.

00:44:06.210 --> 00:44:08.140 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that could happen.

00:44:08.140 --> 00:44:14.640 align:middle line:84%
And the main thing we have to
study is how often that happens.

00:44:14.640 --> 00:44:18.643 align:middle line:90%
But this lemma is still true.

00:44:18.643 --> 00:44:21.450 align:middle line:90%


00:44:21.450 --> 00:44:24.630 align:middle line:84%
This might be a lot
smaller than Xj delta

00:44:24.630 --> 00:44:30.570 align:middle line:84%
because many points that
were far apart in Xj

00:44:30.570 --> 00:44:34.020 align:middle line:84%
may have gotten squished
together in pi t of Xj.

00:44:34.020 --> 00:44:36.270 align:middle line:84%
But this is just the
number of delta balls

00:44:36.270 --> 00:44:42.140 align:middle line:84%
that it takes to
cover the image there.

00:44:42.140 --> 00:44:49.200 align:middle line:90%


00:44:49.200 --> 00:44:52.230 align:middle line:90%
Does that answer your question?

00:44:52.230 --> 00:44:53.350 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:44:53.350 --> 00:45:01.740 align:middle line:84%
Also, in the third image, why
is each delta ball containing

00:45:01.740 --> 00:45:04.540 align:middle line:84%
only the size of
one of those strips?

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:06.210 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Ah, OK.

00:45:06.210 --> 00:45:10.600 align:middle line:84%
So we tuned delta and
r to play together.

00:45:10.600 --> 00:45:13.950 align:middle line:84%
So that we picked r so that
the thickness of this strip

00:45:13.950 --> 00:45:15.420 align:middle line:90%
is delta.

00:45:15.420 --> 00:45:18.030 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: I thought if the
transformation is applied

00:45:18.030 --> 00:45:23.190 align:middle line:84%
multiple times, then you get
multiple e to the minus 2rj

00:45:23.190 --> 00:45:26.310 align:middle line:90%
scale, right?

00:45:26.310 --> 00:45:29.970 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: That's not
wrong, but when we apply it

00:45:29.970 --> 00:45:32.070 align:middle line:84%
multiple times, we're
not changing little r,

00:45:32.070 --> 00:45:34.050 align:middle line:90%
we're just applying a sub r--

00:45:34.050 --> 00:45:36.350 align:middle line:90%
a sub little r multiple times.

00:45:36.350 --> 00:45:40.430 align:middle line:84%
So this picture is describing
what happens in one time,

00:45:40.430 --> 00:45:43.110 align:middle line:84%
and then you could use
this in many rounds.

00:45:43.110 --> 00:45:46.580 align:middle line:84%
So you could use this
lemma over and over again.

00:45:46.580 --> 00:45:48.870 align:middle line:90%
Which is what we'll do.

00:45:48.870 --> 00:45:49.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:45:49.370 --> 00:46:12.890 align:middle line:90%


00:46:12.890 --> 00:46:15.070 align:middle line:84%
Let me change my
notation a little bit.

00:46:15.070 --> 00:46:17.750 align:middle line:90%


00:46:17.750 --> 00:46:20.360 align:middle line:84%
So I was using the letter pi
for this maybe a little bit

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:21.390 align:middle line:90%
prematurely.

00:46:21.390 --> 00:46:23.760 align:middle line:84%
What's clear so far
is that this is a map,

00:46:23.760 --> 00:46:27.980 align:middle line:84%
so I'm going to call
it f1, ft, and f0.

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:29.790 align:middle line:90%
And so then I'll change this.

00:46:29.790 --> 00:46:34.280 align:middle line:90%


00:46:34.280 --> 00:46:34.780 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:34.780 --> 00:46:42.010 align:middle line:90%


00:46:42.010 --> 00:46:42.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:45.820 align:middle line:84%
So now, the next remark
is that these maps look

00:46:45.820 --> 00:46:48.020 align:middle line:90%
a lot like linear projections.

00:46:48.020 --> 00:46:53.050 align:middle line:84%
So remark, ft is
kind of approximately

00:46:53.050 --> 00:46:58.060 align:middle line:90%
an orthogonal projection pi t.

00:46:58.060 --> 00:47:00.050 align:middle line:90%
So let me make a picture.

00:47:00.050 --> 00:47:07.000 align:middle line:84%
So ft does something like this,
and this thickness is delta.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:09.520 align:middle line:90%
This is 1.

00:47:09.520 --> 00:47:13.536 align:middle line:84%
And then pi t would just be an
actual orthogonal projection.

00:47:13.536 --> 00:47:16.750 align:middle line:90%


00:47:16.750 --> 00:47:17.250 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:17.250 --> 00:47:20.708 align:middle line:90%


00:47:20.708 --> 00:47:31.890 align:middle line:84%
So ft is not perfectly
linear, but it is smooth.

00:47:31.890 --> 00:47:37.180 align:middle line:90%


00:47:37.180 --> 00:47:39.655 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:47:39.655 --> 00:47:45.240 align:middle line:84%
So now, here is a proposition--
or exercise about projections.

00:47:45.240 --> 00:47:50.200 align:middle line:84%
It says that if X is in
the unit ball in a plane,

00:47:50.200 --> 00:47:57.820 align:middle line:84%
then you take the average over
all directions, theta and S1,

00:47:57.820 --> 00:48:06.220 align:middle line:84%
of pi theta of X delta that
is at least as big as X delta

00:48:06.220 --> 00:48:06.910 align:middle line:90%
to the 1/2.

00:48:06.910 --> 00:48:09.580 align:middle line:90%


00:48:09.580 --> 00:48:12.700 align:middle line:84%
Here's an example that shows
where the X delta to the 1/2

00:48:12.700 --> 00:48:13.275 align:middle line:90%
comes from.

00:48:13.275 --> 00:48:17.200 align:middle line:90%


00:48:17.200 --> 00:48:19.720 align:middle line:90%
So here's the unit ball.

00:48:19.720 --> 00:48:22.930 align:middle line:84%
And then inside of it,
I take a smaller ball

00:48:22.930 --> 00:48:31.440 align:middle line:84%
and I call that X. So, X is the
ball of some small radius rho

00:48:31.440 --> 00:48:35.640 align:middle line:90%
inside of the ball of radius 1.

00:48:35.640 --> 00:48:36.520 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:41.730 align:middle line:84%
Then when I perform an
orthogonal projection--

00:48:41.730 --> 00:48:44.170 align:middle line:84%
there is pi theta of
X, in any direction

00:48:44.170 --> 00:48:48.270 align:middle line:90%
I'll get a line of length rho.

00:48:48.270 --> 00:48:52.890 align:middle line:84%
So I see that X delta
is like rho over delta

00:48:52.890 --> 00:48:59.520 align:middle line:84%
squared, and pi theta of
X delta-covering number

00:48:59.520 --> 00:49:05.890 align:middle line:84%
is like rho over delta, so this
is the square root of that OK.

00:49:05.890 --> 00:49:08.400 align:middle line:84%
And this is the
best thing to do.

00:49:08.400 --> 00:49:10.410 align:middle line:84%
You could devise
an example where

00:49:10.410 --> 00:49:13.620 align:middle line:84%
in one particular direction,
the compression is much smaller

00:49:13.620 --> 00:49:15.270 align:middle line:90%
than the square root.

00:49:15.270 --> 00:49:18.558 align:middle line:90%
Here's an example like that.

00:49:18.558 --> 00:49:19.058 align:middle line:90%
B1.

00:49:19.058 --> 00:49:21.960 align:middle line:90%


00:49:21.960 --> 00:49:25.690 align:middle line:90%
Here's X. Here's theta.

00:49:25.690 --> 00:49:26.190 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:26.190 --> 00:49:32.370 align:middle line:84%
In this example, pi theta
of X delta is much smaller--

00:49:32.370 --> 00:49:34.050 align:middle line:90%
I'll call this theta 0--

00:49:34.050 --> 00:49:38.840 align:middle line:84%
much smaller than X delta
to the 1/2 for one theta 0.

00:49:38.840 --> 00:49:41.730 align:middle line:90%


00:49:41.730 --> 00:49:44.190 align:middle line:84%
But at least in this picture,
most of the projections

00:49:44.190 --> 00:49:46.510 align:middle line:90%
are way bigger.

00:49:46.510 --> 00:49:47.010 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:49:47.010 --> 00:49:51.340 align:middle line:84%
So it's not super difficult
to check this proposition,

00:49:51.340 --> 00:49:54.240 align:middle line:84%
and I'm going to
make it an exercise.

00:49:54.240 --> 00:49:55.840 align:middle line:84%
I think we're out
of problem sets,

00:49:55.840 --> 00:49:58.955 align:middle line:84%
but if we weren't, this is a
nice one to review the class.

00:49:58.955 --> 00:50:01.800 align:middle line:90%


00:50:01.800 --> 00:50:02.370 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:02.370 --> 00:50:05.700 align:middle line:84%
Another comment is even though
these ft's are not exactly

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:08.310 align:middle line:84%
linear maps, so that we cannot
just literally apply this

00:50:08.310 --> 00:50:12.540 align:middle line:84%
proposition, they are close
enough that by using the proof

00:50:12.540 --> 00:50:16.080 align:middle line:84%
of this, you can
get it for ft, too.

00:50:16.080 --> 00:50:29.490 align:middle line:84%
So remark, the proof
applies to ft. OK.

00:50:29.490 --> 00:50:33.740 align:middle line:90%


00:50:33.740 --> 00:50:36.900 align:middle line:84%
So if we put together this
lemma and this proposition,

00:50:36.900 --> 00:50:39.650 align:middle line:84%
we'll get an estimate about the
delta-covering number of Xj.

00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:55.190 align:middle line:90%


00:50:55.190 --> 00:50:56.471 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:50:56.471 --> 00:50:58.970 align:middle line:84%
So corollary, if we
put these together,

00:50:58.970 --> 00:51:05.150 align:middle line:84%
Xj plus 1 delta-covering number
is at least around delta inverse

00:51:05.150 --> 00:51:08.060 align:middle line:90%
times Xj delta to the 1/2.

00:51:08.060 --> 00:51:11.630 align:middle line:90%


00:51:11.630 --> 00:51:12.950 align:middle line:90%
Proof.

00:51:12.950 --> 00:51:22.040 align:middle line:84%
So Xj plus 1 delta is
at least, by our lemma,

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:28.460 align:middle line:84%
delta inverse times the
average over t of Xj--

00:51:28.460 --> 00:51:34.610 align:middle line:90%
of ft of Xj delta.

00:51:34.610 --> 00:51:40.130 align:middle line:84%
And then by our proposition,
that's at least delta inverse

00:51:40.130 --> 00:51:44.470 align:middle line:84%
times Xj delta to the
1/2, and that's the proof.

00:51:44.470 --> 00:51:47.370 align:middle line:90%


00:51:47.370 --> 00:51:47.870 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:51:47.870 --> 00:51:50.100 align:middle line:84%
So then let's just
track what this means.

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:53.370 align:middle line:90%
So X0 delta would be 1.

00:51:53.370 --> 00:51:57.360 align:middle line:84%
Think about what X0 delta
means, it's one unipotent orbit.

00:51:57.360 --> 00:52:04.760 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, X1 delta would be
at least around delta inverse,

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:13.430 align:middle line:84%
X2 delta would be at least
around delta to the minus 3/2,

00:52:13.430 --> 00:52:19.540 align:middle line:84%
X3 delta be at least around
delta to the minus 1 and 3/4,

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:23.775 align:middle line:84%
and so on, and you'd get pretty
close to delta to the minus 2.

00:52:23.775 --> 00:52:27.485 align:middle line:90%


00:52:27.485 --> 00:52:27.985 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:27.985 --> 00:52:31.113 align:middle line:84%
And delta to the minus 2 would
be like a definite fraction

00:52:31.113 --> 00:52:31.905 align:middle line:90%
of the whole space.

00:52:31.905 --> 00:52:35.590 align:middle line:90%


00:52:35.590 --> 00:52:38.110 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:52:38.110 --> 00:52:41.740 align:middle line:84%
So this proves that a
unipotent orbit that's

00:52:41.740 --> 00:52:46.420 align:middle line:84%
not close to periodic, it
proves that it fills up

00:52:46.420 --> 00:52:50.200 align:middle line:90%
a lot of the homogeneous space.

00:52:50.200 --> 00:52:53.020 align:middle line:90%
And it's not Hedlund's theorem.

00:52:53.020 --> 00:52:53.780 align:middle line:90%
Hold on a second.

00:52:53.780 --> 00:52:56.960 align:middle line:84%
So we didn't prove yet
that the orbit is dense.

00:52:56.960 --> 00:53:00.010 align:middle line:84%
The orbit could be missing
an entire ball that's

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:02.690 align:middle line:84%
like half the size of the space,
and this could still be true.

00:53:02.690 --> 00:53:05.570 align:middle line:84%
But we did prove that the
orbit goes a lot of places.

00:53:05.570 --> 00:53:07.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:09.250 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: In this proof, does--

00:53:09.250 --> 00:53:13.480 align:middle line:84%
since applying it each time
loses some of implicit constant,

00:53:13.480 --> 00:53:15.790 align:middle line:84%
how do we know that it's
not becoming dense and just,

00:53:15.790 --> 00:53:19.940 align:middle line:84%
like, an infinitesimally small
region of this whole space?

00:53:19.940 --> 00:53:25.075 align:middle line:90%


00:53:25.075 --> 00:53:25.950 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: Right.

00:53:25.950 --> 00:53:28.200 align:middle line:84%
So I think the question is
like, we didn't actually

00:53:28.200 --> 00:53:30.760 align:middle line:84%
get to a constant times
delta to the minus 2,

00:53:30.760 --> 00:53:33.670 align:middle line:84%
and if I tried to do this
infinitely many times,

00:53:33.670 --> 00:53:35.620 align:middle line:84%
I would be losing a
constant each time.

00:53:35.620 --> 00:53:36.790 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's right.

00:53:36.790 --> 00:53:40.860 align:middle line:84%
So imagine doing this 10
times and we get delta

00:53:40.860 --> 00:53:42.910 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 1.99.

00:53:42.910 --> 00:53:46.590 align:middle line:84%
And that's what the
method proves so far.

00:53:46.590 --> 00:53:49.350 align:middle line:84%
So stronger things are
true, but this method

00:53:49.350 --> 00:53:52.740 align:middle line:90%
doesn't prove them yet.

00:53:52.740 --> 00:54:02.790 align:middle line:84%
So remark, this doesn't show
that the orbit is actually

00:54:02.790 --> 00:54:12.290 align:middle line:84%
dense, and so maybe question,
could the orbit do this?

00:54:12.290 --> 00:54:14.880 align:middle line:90%


00:54:14.880 --> 00:54:17.740 align:middle line:84%
So here's our homogeneous
space, there's a cusp,

00:54:17.740 --> 00:54:19.830 align:middle line:90%
but it's not that important.

00:54:19.830 --> 00:54:24.340 align:middle line:84%
And then the orbit
goes around a good bit,

00:54:24.340 --> 00:54:27.750 align:middle line:84%
but it only ever goes
around over here,

00:54:27.750 --> 00:54:29.320 align:middle line:90%
and it never goes over there.

00:54:29.320 --> 00:54:33.180 align:middle line:84%
So this proof doesn't
say anything about that.

00:54:33.180 --> 00:54:34.404 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:54:34.404 --> 00:54:39.180 align:middle line:84%
So, as far as I know, to
finish Hedlund's theorem

00:54:39.180 --> 00:54:42.960 align:middle line:84%
requires another step that
is based on different ideas

00:54:42.960 --> 00:54:45.540 align:middle line:90%
from these ideas.

00:54:45.540 --> 00:54:48.930 align:middle line:84%
So there's more to homogeneous
dynamics than this story,

00:54:48.930 --> 00:54:51.400 align:middle line:84%
but we did still learn
something interesting.

00:54:51.400 --> 00:54:56.320 align:middle line:90%


00:54:56.320 --> 00:54:56.820 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:54:56.820 --> 00:55:02.670 align:middle line:90%


00:55:02.670 --> 00:55:03.960 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:55:03.960 --> 00:55:06.450 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Do how
close as possible

00:55:06.450 --> 00:55:09.240 align:middle line:84%
to get to the full theorem
by trying to optimize all

00:55:09.240 --> 00:55:10.630 align:middle line:90%
the constants in this proof?

00:55:10.630 --> 00:55:13.530 align:middle line:90%


00:55:13.530 --> 00:55:14.280 align:middle line:90%
LAWRENCE GUTH: OK.

00:55:14.280 --> 00:55:16.738 align:middle line:84%
So there are two things that
we might like to improve here.

00:55:16.738 --> 00:55:19.520 align:middle line:84%
So the question is, how close
can we get to the full theorem

00:55:19.520 --> 00:55:22.760 align:middle line:84%
by optimizing the argument
that we've been talking about?

00:55:22.760 --> 00:55:24.440 align:middle line:84%
So one thing that
you might like is

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:29.150 align:middle line:84%
you might like to actually
get to delta to the minus 2.

00:55:29.150 --> 00:55:33.390 align:middle line:84%
That still wouldn't necessarily
rule out this possibility,

00:55:33.390 --> 00:55:35.840 align:middle line:90%
but it would be interesting.

00:55:35.840 --> 00:55:43.430 align:middle line:84%
And if you look at this
proposition, one thing

00:55:43.430 --> 00:55:46.400 align:middle line:84%
that you notice, that
this proposition is

00:55:46.400 --> 00:55:48.540 align:middle line:90%
sharp in this very clumped case.

00:55:48.540 --> 00:55:51.780 align:middle line:84%
And if you remember back to
the early months of our class,

00:55:51.780 --> 00:55:55.550 align:middle line:84%
if x was not so
compressed, then there

00:55:55.550 --> 00:55:57.360 align:middle line:90%
would be even better estimates.

00:55:57.360 --> 00:56:02.160 align:middle line:84%
So if you knew as an input
that x is not too clustered,

00:56:02.160 --> 00:56:04.680 align:middle line:84%
then you could get all the
way to delta to the minus 2

00:56:04.680 --> 00:56:09.020 align:middle line:84%
in one step or two
steps or something.

00:56:09.020 --> 00:56:11.430 align:middle line:84%
And so you might
try to track that.

00:56:11.430 --> 00:56:14.040 align:middle line:84%
You might try to track not
just the delta-covering number,

00:56:14.040 --> 00:56:16.980 align:middle line:84%
but also the rho-covering number
for different delta and rho,

00:56:16.980 --> 00:56:19.470 align:middle line:84%
and then you could take
advantage of this clustering.

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:24.980 align:middle line:84%
And I am not positive, but I
think it is a reasonable 18-156

00:56:24.980 --> 00:56:29.870 align:middle line:84%
project to try to use that
to get all the way to delta

00:56:29.870 --> 00:56:30.730 align:middle line:90%
to the minus 2.

00:56:30.730 --> 00:56:33.260 align:middle line:90%


00:56:33.260 --> 00:56:34.970 align:middle line:90%
Oh.

00:56:34.970 --> 00:56:38.780 align:middle line:84%
Even if you got a constant
times delta to the minus 2,

00:56:38.780 --> 00:56:42.830 align:middle line:84%
it would still not
be obvious to me

00:56:42.830 --> 00:56:44.900 align:middle line:84%
that you filled
the entire manifold

00:56:44.900 --> 00:56:46.590 align:middle line:84%
and that you're
not missing a ball.

00:56:46.590 --> 00:56:51.060 align:middle line:84%
And I thought about it
yesterday and today,

00:56:51.060 --> 00:56:54.650 align:middle line:84%
and I don't have a good
understanding yet of what you

00:56:54.650 --> 00:56:57.680 align:middle line:90%
need to get everywhere.

00:56:57.680 --> 00:57:01.970 align:middle line:84%
So I would be interested to
learn if people have thoughts

00:57:01.970 --> 00:57:03.870 align:middle line:90%
about it or know about it.

00:57:03.870 --> 00:57:07.010 align:middle line:90%


00:57:07.010 --> 00:57:09.790 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:09.790 --> 00:57:11.560 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

00:57:11.560 --> 00:57:13.180 align:middle line:84%
So I think that
there are actually

00:57:13.180 --> 00:57:15.470 align:middle line:84%
are a bunch of ways to
prove Hedlund's theorem,

00:57:15.470 --> 00:57:19.360 align:middle line:84%
and this is not one that I
have seen in the literature.

00:57:19.360 --> 00:57:24.940 align:middle line:84%
And all of these problems
become more difficult and maybe

00:57:24.940 --> 00:57:29.350 align:middle line:84%
more interesting when you
go to higher dimensions.

00:57:29.350 --> 00:57:32.560 align:middle line:84%
So the projection theory also
becomes more difficult and more

00:57:32.560 --> 00:57:34.040 align:middle line:84%
interesting in
higher dimensions,

00:57:34.040 --> 00:57:36.550 align:middle line:84%
and I wanted, in the
last part of the class,

00:57:36.550 --> 00:57:38.860 align:middle line:90%
to just show you what happens.

00:57:38.860 --> 00:57:42.368 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, we
will see a new question

00:57:42.368 --> 00:57:44.410 align:middle line:84%
about projection theory
that we haven't mentioned

00:57:44.410 --> 00:57:46.300 align:middle line:84%
so far in this class,
but which I think

00:57:46.300 --> 00:57:47.610 align:middle line:90%
is a really cool question.

00:57:47.610 --> 00:57:50.990 align:middle line:90%


00:57:50.990 --> 00:57:51.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:57:51.490 --> 00:58:15.430 align:middle line:90%


00:58:15.430 --> 00:58:17.320 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:17.320 --> 00:58:19.040 align:middle line:90%
So let me put it this way.

00:58:19.040 --> 00:58:23.400 align:middle line:90%
What about SLn R?

00:58:23.400 --> 00:58:26.957 align:middle line:90%


00:58:26.957 --> 00:58:27.457 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:58:27.457 --> 00:58:31.240 align:middle line:90%


00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:35.120 align:middle line:84%
So, I'm going to take a
somewhat specific example,

00:58:35.120 --> 00:58:37.420 align:middle line:84%
although I think most
of what we'll say then

00:58:37.420 --> 00:58:38.600 align:middle line:90%
would work for any n.

00:58:38.600 --> 00:58:42.160 align:middle line:84%
So for example, we
could have SL3 R

00:58:42.160 --> 00:58:48.130 align:middle line:84%
for our G, gamma
could be SL3 z, and U

00:58:48.130 --> 00:58:53.490 align:middle line:84%
could be the unipotent group of
matrices that look like this.

00:58:53.490 --> 00:58:57.670 align:middle line:90%


00:58:57.670 --> 00:59:00.700 align:middle line:84%
So from what I
understand, there are

00:59:00.700 --> 00:59:03.610 align:middle line:84%
several different one-parameter
unipotent subgroups

00:59:03.610 --> 00:59:06.280 align:middle line:84%
of SL3 R. They're slightly
different from each other.

00:59:06.280 --> 00:59:09.210 align:middle line:84%
And this one is
particularly well-studied

00:59:09.210 --> 00:59:11.230 align:middle line:84%
in the homogeneous
dynamics community

00:59:11.230 --> 00:59:12.690 align:middle line:84%
because it's the
one that comes up

00:59:12.690 --> 00:59:17.460 align:middle line:84%
in the Oppenheim conjecture
about quadratic forms.

00:59:17.460 --> 00:59:21.030 align:middle line:84%
But anyway, so we have this
one-parameter subgroup.

00:59:21.030 --> 00:59:24.780 align:middle line:90%
And so let's call this u sub t.

00:59:24.780 --> 00:59:25.420 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:25.420 --> 00:59:28.560 align:middle line:84%
So our basic setup
with conjugating

00:59:28.560 --> 00:59:31.150 align:middle line:84%
by a diagonal
matrix, that works.

00:59:31.150 --> 00:59:36.540 align:middle line:84%
And the relevant diagonal
matrix is this matrix.

00:59:36.540 --> 00:59:37.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:37.060 --> 00:59:41.520 align:middle line:84%
And then you can check that
a sub r u sub t a sub r

00:59:41.520 --> 00:59:44.760 align:middle line:90%
inverse is u sub e to the r t.

00:59:44.760 --> 00:59:47.440 align:middle line:84%
Turns out to be e to the
r t, not e to the 2r t,

00:59:47.440 --> 00:59:52.050 align:middle line:90%
but that's not too big a deal.

00:59:52.050 --> 00:59:53.826 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:59:53.826 --> 01:00:02.463 align:middle line:84%
So now, we have a bunch of
unipotent orbits like before.

01:00:02.463 --> 01:00:08.960 align:middle line:90%


01:00:08.960 --> 01:00:11.060 align:middle line:84%
It was a bunch of
unipotent orbits.

01:00:11.060 --> 01:00:17.570 align:middle line:84%
But the dimension of our
group is 8 instead of 3.

01:00:17.570 --> 01:00:20.930 align:middle line:84%
And so we have the
direction along the orbits,

01:00:20.930 --> 01:00:24.360 align:middle line:84%
t equals 0 up to t equals 1,
that's still one-dimensional.

01:00:24.360 --> 01:00:27.080 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is a
seven-dimensional ball

01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:29.360 align:middle line:90%
instead of a disc.

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:30.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:00:30.300 --> 01:00:33.260 align:middle line:90%
So now, we apply--

01:00:33.260 --> 01:00:41.390 align:middle line:84%
we study the action
of Lar inverse.

01:00:41.390 --> 01:00:45.510 align:middle line:84%
And we'll have a
picture like this.

01:00:45.510 --> 01:00:46.010 align:middle line:90%
f1.

01:00:46.010 --> 01:00:49.340 align:middle line:90%


01:00:49.340 --> 01:00:51.530 align:middle line:90%
f0.

01:00:51.530 --> 01:00:55.170 align:middle line:84%
And, OK, something
here will happen,

01:00:55.170 --> 01:00:57.145 align:middle line:84%
and something different
here will happen.

01:00:57.145 --> 01:01:01.250 align:middle line:90%


01:01:01.250 --> 01:01:02.465 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:02.465 --> 01:01:04.653 align:middle line:84%
So you can study the
singular values--

01:01:04.653 --> 01:01:07.910 align:middle line:90%


01:01:07.910 --> 01:01:12.630 align:middle line:84%
the singular values--
of Lar inverse.

01:01:12.630 --> 01:01:17.630 align:middle line:84%
And those are equal to the
singular values of conjugation

01:01:17.630 --> 01:01:18.540 align:middle line:90%
by ar.

01:01:18.540 --> 01:01:22.470 align:middle line:84%
So conjugation by ar is a very
nice operation on matrices,

01:01:22.470 --> 01:01:24.270 align:middle line:84%
you can write it down
and see what happens.

01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:26.670 align:middle line:84%
And you can compute
these singular values.

01:01:26.670 --> 01:01:29.540 align:middle line:90%
And they are as follows.

01:01:29.540 --> 01:01:35.490 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus 2r, e to the
minus r, e to the minus r, 1, 1,

01:01:35.490 --> 01:01:38.500 align:middle line:84%
e to the r, e to
the r, e to the 2.

01:01:38.500 --> 01:01:41.120 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.120 --> 01:01:45.830 align:middle line:84%
I won't do it on the board,
but I promise it's not hard.

01:01:45.830 --> 01:01:46.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:46.530 --> 01:01:50.810 align:middle line:84%
Now one of these singular values
corresponds to the U-direction.

01:01:50.810 --> 01:01:54.980 align:middle line:84%
So, little n is
the vector that's

01:01:54.980 --> 01:02:01.840 align:middle line:84%
the tangent vector to the
group u at the identity.

01:02:01.840 --> 01:02:03.850 align:middle line:90%
And so little n is--

01:02:03.850 --> 01:02:06.140 align:middle line:84%
it's not super important
what the formula is,

01:02:06.140 --> 01:02:08.770 align:middle line:84%
but if you differentiate that,
you'll see that the tangent

01:02:08.770 --> 01:02:10.210 align:middle line:90%
vector is that.

01:02:10.210 --> 01:02:14.770 align:middle line:90%
And that's one of these guys.

01:02:14.770 --> 01:02:19.250 align:middle line:84%
So as before, the direction
of the orbits is expanding.

01:02:19.250 --> 01:02:25.010 align:middle line:84%
And then on the B 7, we have
the other seven directions.

01:02:25.010 --> 01:02:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So this thing over here is
an ellipsoid with axes e

01:02:32.050 --> 01:02:36.250 align:middle line:84%
to the minus 2r, e to the minus
r, e to the minus r, 1, 1,

01:02:36.250 --> 01:02:38.580 align:middle line:90%
e to the r, e to the 2.

01:02:38.580 --> 01:02:42.280 align:middle line:90%


01:02:42.280 --> 01:02:43.756 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:43.756 --> 01:02:47.350 align:middle line:84%
So, as we go from here
to here, these maps

01:02:47.350 --> 01:02:49.700 align:middle line:84%
are not exactly linear, but
they're close to linear,

01:02:49.700 --> 01:02:52.840 align:middle line:84%
they're close to linear maps,
and they stretch some directions

01:02:52.840 --> 01:02:55.185 align:middle line:84%
and they compress other
directions by these amounts.

01:02:55.185 --> 01:02:58.030 align:middle line:90%


01:02:58.030 --> 01:02:59.998 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:02:59.998 --> 01:03:03.435 align:middle line:84%
So, what is different
from before?

01:03:03.435 --> 01:03:06.790 align:middle line:90%


01:03:06.790 --> 01:03:07.360 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:07.360 --> 01:03:11.680 align:middle line:84%
One difference is that
this thing is not exactly

01:03:11.680 --> 01:03:13.136 align:middle line:90%
a projection.

01:03:13.136 --> 01:03:30.280 align:middle line:90%


01:03:30.280 --> 01:03:32.870 align:middle line:84%
But that's not the most
important difference.

01:03:32.870 --> 01:03:36.640 align:middle line:90%


01:03:36.640 --> 01:03:38.355 align:middle line:90%
So differences from last time.

01:03:38.355 --> 01:03:44.390 align:middle line:90%


01:03:44.390 --> 01:03:44.890 align:middle line:90%
Right.

01:03:44.890 --> 01:03:51.100 align:middle line:84%
So if we had an
approximate projection that

01:03:51.100 --> 01:03:57.060 align:middle line:84%
went from the 7 ball to some
vector space V of dimension

01:03:57.060 --> 01:04:00.180 align:middle line:84%
three, say-- so four
dimensions are getting squished

01:04:00.180 --> 01:04:02.670 align:middle line:84%
and three dimensions
are staying as they are,

01:04:02.670 --> 01:04:10.800 align:middle line:84%
that would be approximately a
linear map with singular values

01:04:10.800 --> 01:04:14.205 align:middle line:84%
e to the minus r, e to the
minus r, e to the minus r,

01:04:14.205 --> 01:04:17.220 align:middle line:90%
e to the minus r, 1, 1, 1.

01:04:17.220 --> 01:04:22.205 align:middle line:84%
If I had a linear map like
that, these guys are almost 0.

01:04:22.205 --> 01:04:24.580 align:middle line:84%
So these are the four directions
that are being squished,

01:04:24.580 --> 01:04:27.180 align:middle line:84%
these are the three directions
that are staying the same.

01:04:27.180 --> 01:04:30.670 align:middle line:84%
The list of singular values
here is not quite like that.

01:04:30.670 --> 01:04:33.810 align:middle line:84%
Some of them are bigger than
1, we didn't have that before.

01:04:33.810 --> 01:04:36.660 align:middle line:84%
And the ones that are--
some of them are equal to 1.

01:04:36.660 --> 01:04:40.050 align:middle line:84%
The ones that are smaller than
1 have two different scales.

01:04:40.050 --> 01:04:42.040 align:middle line:84%
So that's a little
bit more complicated,

01:04:42.040 --> 01:04:43.925 align:middle line:90%
but I don't want to focus on it.

01:04:43.925 --> 01:04:46.560 align:middle line:90%


01:04:46.560 --> 01:04:51.850 align:middle line:84%
So, our singular values are
a little more complicated.

01:04:51.850 --> 01:04:59.040 align:middle line:90%


01:04:59.040 --> 01:04:59.820 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:04:59.820 --> 01:05:00.965 align:middle line:90%
Let's ignore that.

01:05:00.965 --> 01:05:02.340 align:middle line:84%
Suppose each of
these linear maps

01:05:02.340 --> 01:05:04.200 align:middle line:84%
actually had those
singular values,

01:05:04.200 --> 01:05:07.060 align:middle line:84%
so it was more like what we were
used to in projection theory.

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:08.820 align:middle line:84%
There would be a
different-- there

01:05:08.820 --> 01:05:12.870 align:middle line:84%
would be another difference from
before, which is more important.

01:05:12.870 --> 01:05:14.940 align:middle line:90%
So number 1.

01:05:14.940 --> 01:05:20.730 align:middle line:84%
Number 2, we still have
only a one parameter family

01:05:20.730 --> 01:05:22.013 align:middle line:90%
of linear maps.

01:05:22.013 --> 01:05:25.650 align:middle line:90%


01:05:25.650 --> 01:05:26.910 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:26.910 --> 01:05:32.640 align:middle line:84%
So before, when we talked about
projections from B 7 to V--

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:36.260 align:middle line:84%
to the three-dimensional vector
space, we talked about all

01:05:36.260 --> 01:05:36.760 align:middle line:90%
of them.

01:05:36.760 --> 01:05:39.330 align:middle line:84%
If you look at all of
the projections from B 7

01:05:39.330 --> 01:05:41.080 align:middle line:84%
to the three-dimensional
vector spaces,

01:05:41.080 --> 01:05:43.290 align:middle line:84%
then something nice
happens most of the time.

01:05:43.290 --> 01:05:45.820 align:middle line:90%
But we don't have all of them.

01:05:45.820 --> 01:05:49.920 align:middle line:84%
We just have a very
thin subfamily.

01:05:49.920 --> 01:05:54.480 align:middle line:84%
So this is not all
of the projections.

01:05:54.480 --> 01:05:57.890 align:middle line:90%


01:05:57.890 --> 01:05:58.820 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:05:58.820 --> 01:05:59.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:05:59.760 --> 01:06:02.900 align:middle line:84%
So there's also a
cosmetic complication

01:06:02.900 --> 01:06:06.410 align:middle line:84%
that 7 is a lot of dimensions
and there are a lot of numbers,

01:06:06.410 --> 01:06:09.030 align:middle line:84%
but that's not that
important, it's just a pain.

01:06:09.030 --> 01:06:12.390 align:middle line:84%
But these are this
to some extent,

01:06:12.390 --> 01:06:16.730 align:middle line:84%
and this is a really fundamental
conceptual difference.

01:06:16.730 --> 01:06:19.940 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to show you not
this problem, but the simplest

01:06:19.940 --> 01:06:23.160 align:middle line:90%
problem of this type.

01:06:23.160 --> 01:06:25.885 align:middle line:84%
Which is called the
restricted projection problem.

01:06:25.885 --> 01:06:49.620 align:middle line:90%


01:06:49.620 --> 01:06:50.120 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:06:50.120 --> 01:07:00.520 align:middle line:90%


01:07:00.520 --> 01:07:01.160 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:07:01.160 --> 01:07:04.550 align:middle line:84%
So this question, which I
think is a cool question,

01:07:04.550 --> 01:07:09.940 align:middle line:84%
was raised by Fassler, Katrin
Fassler, and Tuomas Orponen

01:07:09.940 --> 01:07:13.060 align:middle line:90%
in 2013.

01:07:13.060 --> 01:07:15.140 align:middle line:90%
And the question is like this.

01:07:15.140 --> 01:07:19.640 align:middle line:90%
So here's the 2 sphere.

01:07:19.640 --> 01:07:22.300 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to be doing
projection theory in three

01:07:22.300 --> 01:07:24.880 align:middle line:84%
dimensions, in R 3, so the
different directions are

01:07:24.880 --> 01:07:26.450 align:middle line:90%
parametrized by the 2 sphere.

01:07:26.450 --> 01:07:28.550 align:middle line:84%
But we're not going to
project in all of them,

01:07:28.550 --> 01:07:33.190 align:middle line:84%
we're just going to pick
some curve gamma and project

01:07:33.190 --> 01:07:34.780 align:middle line:90%
in the directions of gamma.

01:07:34.780 --> 01:07:37.780 align:middle line:84%
So gamma contained
in S2 is a curve.

01:07:37.780 --> 01:07:41.470 align:middle line:90%


01:07:41.470 --> 01:07:44.680 align:middle line:90%
The question is like this.

01:07:44.680 --> 01:07:48.590 align:middle line:84%
If X is contained
in the unit 3 ball,

01:07:48.590 --> 01:07:52.802 align:middle line:84%
and let's say x is
a delta, s, C set--

01:07:52.802 --> 01:07:54.260 align:middle line:84%
we'll put-- to make
it interesting,

01:07:54.260 --> 01:07:56.600 align:middle line:84%
we put some kind of
non-concentration condition,

01:07:56.600 --> 01:08:00.910 align:middle line:84%
and this is the one that they
had in their paper, basically.

01:08:00.910 --> 01:08:01.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:01.960 --> 01:08:10.990 align:middle line:84%
Then estimate the average
over all the directions

01:08:10.990 --> 01:08:18.250 align:middle line:84%
in gamma of the pi theta
of X delta-covering number.

01:08:18.250 --> 01:08:23.479 align:middle line:84%
OK, so pi-- so theta is a
direction, an element of S 2,

01:08:23.479 --> 01:08:27.010 align:middle line:84%
and pi theta is the
orthogonal projection

01:08:27.010 --> 01:08:28.939 align:middle line:90%
from R 3 to theta perp.

01:08:28.939 --> 01:08:33.700 align:middle line:84%
So from three dimensions
to two dimensions.

01:08:33.700 --> 01:08:36.460 align:middle line:90%
So estimate the average of that.

01:08:36.460 --> 01:08:39.490 align:middle line:90%
So we still have that--

01:08:39.490 --> 01:08:41.350 align:middle line:90%
I erased the wrong thing.

01:08:41.350 --> 01:08:42.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:08:42.020 --> 01:08:44.229 align:middle line:84%
On this very board, not
two minutes ago, there

01:08:44.229 --> 01:08:47.760 align:middle line:84%
was a proposition that said
if you had a set in R 2,

01:08:47.760 --> 01:08:50.260 align:middle line:84%
and you projected it in
all the different angles,

01:08:50.260 --> 01:08:52.319 align:middle line:84%
then on average, the
delta-covering number

01:08:52.319 --> 01:08:54.600 align:middle line:84%
of the projection was at
least something or another.

01:08:54.600 --> 01:08:57.090 align:middle line:84%
So this is like
an analog of that

01:08:57.090 --> 01:09:00.490 align:middle line:84%
in three dimensions for a set
with the spacing condition,

01:09:00.490 --> 01:09:02.310 align:middle line:84%
but with the key
difference that we're not

01:09:02.310 --> 01:09:04.410 align:middle line:84%
averaging over
all of them, we're

01:09:04.410 --> 01:09:09.540 align:middle line:84%
only averaging over the ones
in a particular curve gamma.

01:09:09.540 --> 01:09:10.300 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:09:10.300 --> 01:09:12.750 align:middle line:84%
Now, an interesting
thing about this question

01:09:12.750 --> 01:09:15.640 align:middle line:84%
is that it matters what
the curve gamma is.

01:09:15.640 --> 01:09:17.520 align:middle line:84%
And in particular,
there's a big difference

01:09:17.520 --> 01:09:20.910 align:middle line:84%
between an equator, which
is like a straight line

01:09:20.910 --> 01:09:26.310 align:middle line:84%
on the sphere, and a
non-degenerate, or curved gamma.

01:09:26.310 --> 01:09:32.609 align:middle line:84%
So the answer depends
on whether gamma--

01:09:32.609 --> 01:09:33.899 align:middle line:90%
gamma is the equator--

01:09:33.899 --> 01:09:39.149 align:middle line:84%
is one extreme or
gamma non-degenerate

01:09:39.149 --> 01:09:41.612 align:middle line:90%
is another extreme.

01:09:41.612 --> 01:09:43.779 align:middle line:84%
Instead of writing the
definition of non-degenerate,

01:09:43.779 --> 01:09:46.600 align:middle line:84%
let me just give you one example
of a non-degenerate curve.

01:09:46.600 --> 01:09:50.609 align:middle line:84%
So, an example of a
non-degenerate curve is gamma is

01:09:50.609 --> 01:09:55.530 align:middle line:84%
equal to the set of theta in S
2 so that the third component

01:09:55.530 --> 01:09:56.550 align:middle line:90%
of theta is 1/2.

01:09:56.550 --> 01:10:01.555 align:middle line:90%


01:10:01.555 --> 01:10:02.055 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:02.055 --> 01:10:07.590 align:middle line:84%
So it looks like the boundary
of the spherical cap.

01:10:07.590 --> 01:10:08.260 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:08.260 --> 01:10:11.495 align:middle line:84%
So let me show you how these
are different from each other.

01:10:11.495 --> 01:10:33.565 align:middle line:90%


01:10:33.565 --> 01:10:34.065 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:34.065 --> 01:10:37.080 align:middle line:90%
So example.

01:10:37.080 --> 01:10:40.480 align:middle line:84%
Say gamma is the
equator and S is 2.

01:10:40.480 --> 01:10:42.980 align:middle line:84%
So we have a, quote unquote,
"two-dimensional set,"

01:10:42.980 --> 01:10:44.325 align:middle line:90%
delta 2 set.

01:10:44.325 --> 01:10:44.825 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:10:44.825 --> 01:10:51.170 align:middle line:84%
So our set X is going to
be a delta-by-1-by-1 slab.

01:10:51.170 --> 01:11:00.740 align:middle line:84%
So it looks-- and so imagine
that the two big directions are

01:11:00.740 --> 01:11:03.500 align:middle line:84%
in the plane of the blackboard,
and the slab is sticking out

01:11:03.500 --> 01:11:05.900 align:middle line:84%
of the blackboard by
a little bit delta.

01:11:05.900 --> 01:11:06.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:06.570 --> 01:11:08.450 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's an
equator of directions

01:11:08.450 --> 01:11:10.400 align:middle line:84%
that we're going to
project in, and think

01:11:10.400 --> 01:11:14.150 align:middle line:84%
of that as the equator that's
like the sphere with center

01:11:14.150 --> 01:11:16.760 align:middle line:84%
at the blackboard, intersected
the sphere with the blackboard,

01:11:16.760 --> 01:11:18.440 align:middle line:90%
you would get a circle.

01:11:18.440 --> 01:11:22.430 align:middle line:90%
So here's gamma.

01:11:22.430 --> 01:11:30.140 align:middle line:84%
So now, if theta is in gamma,
then the projection of X

01:11:30.140 --> 01:11:33.470 align:middle line:90%
is a delta-by-1 rectangle.

01:11:33.470 --> 01:11:34.850 align:middle line:84%
So there's a circle
of directions

01:11:34.850 --> 01:11:37.100 align:middle line:84%
where if you project
this slab, you just

01:11:37.100 --> 01:11:39.210 align:middle line:90%
get a delta-by-1 rectangle.

01:11:39.210 --> 01:11:42.020 align:middle line:90%


01:11:42.020 --> 01:11:43.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:11:43.280 --> 01:11:53.030 align:middle line:84%
So then we see that the
average pi theta of x delta

01:11:53.030 --> 01:11:54.700 align:middle line:90%
is like delta inverse.

01:11:54.700 --> 01:11:59.520 align:middle line:90%


01:11:59.520 --> 01:12:00.020 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:00.020 --> 01:12:05.480 align:middle line:90%


01:12:05.480 --> 01:12:06.030 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:06.030 --> 01:12:09.680 align:middle line:84%
Now there's no obvious
version of this example

01:12:09.680 --> 01:12:14.090 align:middle line:84%
where gamma is that curve
that's up near the top.

01:12:14.090 --> 01:12:16.040 align:middle line:90%
And the difference is--

01:12:16.040 --> 01:12:20.540 align:middle line:84%
so if you're projecting
in a certain direction,

01:12:20.540 --> 01:12:23.750 align:middle line:84%
then the fibers are like
lines in that direction.

01:12:23.750 --> 01:12:26.750 align:middle line:84%
And so what's special here
is that all of these lines

01:12:26.750 --> 01:12:30.740 align:middle line:84%
are coplanar, and so you can
have a planar object that

01:12:30.740 --> 01:12:32.450 align:middle line:90%
has a lot that--

01:12:32.450 --> 01:12:34.910 align:middle line:84%
where these lines
intersected a lot.

01:12:34.910 --> 01:12:38.210 align:middle line:84%
And instead, when we
have those directions,

01:12:38.210 --> 01:12:40.690 align:middle line:84%
then all of our
lines make an angle

01:12:40.690 --> 01:12:42.920 align:middle line:84%
of 45 degrees with
the horizontal.

01:12:42.920 --> 01:12:45.370 align:middle line:90%
They're like light cones.

01:12:45.370 --> 01:12:49.780 align:middle line:84%
And they just don't fit
together in the same nice way

01:12:49.780 --> 01:12:51.790 align:middle line:84%
that coplanar
lines fit together.

01:12:51.790 --> 01:12:53.950 align:middle line:90%
So it makes a difference.

01:12:53.950 --> 01:12:56.915 align:middle line:84%
And Fassler and
Orponen, they proved

01:12:56.915 --> 01:12:58.040 align:middle line:90%
that it makes a difference.

01:12:58.040 --> 01:13:00.790 align:middle line:84%
So they proved some bounds for
that thing that are strictly

01:13:00.790 --> 01:13:01.970 align:middle line:90%
bigger than this thing.

01:13:01.970 --> 01:13:07.870 align:middle line:84%
But it took a while to figure
out what is the sharpest bound.

01:13:07.870 --> 01:13:10.990 align:middle line:84%
And that was figured
out some time later

01:13:10.990 --> 01:13:17.830 align:middle line:84%
in a paper of six authors,
Shengwen Gan Shaoming Guo me,

01:13:17.830 --> 01:13:22.600 align:middle line:84%
Terence Harris, Dominique
Maldague, and Hong Wang,

01:13:22.600 --> 01:13:25.870 align:middle line:84%
many of whom were here working
on it at various times.

01:13:25.870 --> 01:13:26.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:13:26.690 --> 01:13:28.780 align:middle line:90%
And we proved--

01:13:28.780 --> 01:13:31.060 align:middle line:90%
I'll just do a special case.

01:13:31.060 --> 01:13:44.820 align:middle line:84%
So if XCB 3 is a delta, 2, C
set and gamma is non-degenerate,

01:13:44.820 --> 01:13:49.830 align:middle line:84%
like this example above,
then the average theta

01:13:49.830 --> 01:13:54.660 align:middle line:84%
in gamma of pi theta of
X delta-covering number

01:13:54.660 --> 01:13:58.925 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than C epsilon delta
to the negative 2 plus epsilon.

01:13:58.925 --> 01:14:02.986 align:middle line:90%


01:14:02.986 --> 01:14:03.800 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:03.800 --> 01:14:05.550 align:middle line:84%
And the best thing you
could hope for here

01:14:05.550 --> 01:14:08.160 align:middle line:84%
is delta to the
minus 2 because x

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:10.260 align:middle line:84%
itself probably has
delta-covering number

01:14:10.260 --> 01:14:12.120 align:middle line:90%
delta to the minus 2.

01:14:12.120 --> 01:14:16.535 align:middle line:84%
So up to small issues that--
this is the Sharpe theorem.

01:14:16.535 --> 01:14:19.380 align:middle line:90%


01:14:19.380 --> 01:14:21.060 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:21.060 --> 01:14:24.240 align:middle line:84%
This proof is based on some
version of the Fourier analysis

01:14:24.240 --> 01:14:26.880 align:middle line:84%
method, but it's a
more difficult version

01:14:26.880 --> 01:14:28.216 align:middle line:90%
that involves decoupling.

01:14:28.216 --> 01:14:42.660 align:middle line:90%


01:14:42.660 --> 01:14:45.210 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:14:45.210 --> 01:14:46.200 align:middle line:90%
Cool.

01:14:46.200 --> 01:14:50.520 align:middle line:84%
So this connection between
projection theory and--

01:14:50.520 --> 01:14:52.890 align:middle line:84%
between homogeneous dynamics
and projection theory

01:14:52.890 --> 01:14:55.770 align:middle line:84%
was discovered by Elon
Lindenstrauss and Amir

01:14:55.770 --> 01:15:01.410 align:middle line:84%
Mohammadi, who were working on
quantitative estimates for how

01:15:01.410 --> 01:15:04.870 align:middle line:84%
unipotent orbits become
dense in this setup.

01:15:04.870 --> 01:15:06.780 align:middle line:84%
And they realized
this connection

01:15:06.780 --> 01:15:09.670 align:middle line:84%
with projection theory, and
they found the literature,

01:15:09.670 --> 01:15:12.090 align:middle line:84%
they found the paper
by Fassler and Orponen

01:15:12.090 --> 01:15:13.810 align:middle line:90%
and all the follow-up papers.

01:15:13.810 --> 01:15:17.370 align:middle line:84%
And they used those tools to
prove quantitative estimates

01:15:17.370 --> 01:15:20.760 align:middle line:84%
about how these
unipotent orbits mix.

01:15:20.760 --> 01:15:21.308 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:15:21.308 --> 01:15:23.350 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: There's a question
of projection theory

01:15:23.350 --> 01:15:27.540 align:middle line:84%
where each unipotent element
induces a different projection.

01:15:27.540 --> 01:15:31.710 align:middle line:84%
Is that set of projections dense
in the whole-space projections,

01:15:31.710 --> 01:15:34.020 align:middle line:90%
or is it some non-dense subset?

01:15:34.020 --> 01:15:36.000 align:middle line:84%
LAWRENCE GUTH: No, it's
some non-dense subset.

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:39.180 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, so here, t is
going from 0 to 1.

01:15:39.180 --> 01:15:42.650 align:middle line:84%
For each t, we have more
or less a projection.

01:15:42.650 --> 01:15:50.210 align:middle line:84%
And so we have a smooth curve
of length 1 in the space of--

01:15:50.210 --> 01:15:54.260 align:middle line:84%
or not exactly projections,
but the space of linear maps.

01:15:54.260 --> 01:15:57.500 align:middle line:84%
And so it is not, in any
sense, becoming dense

01:15:57.500 --> 01:15:58.680 align:middle line:90%
in the space of linear maps.

01:15:58.680 --> 01:16:00.660 align:middle line:84%
It's really just a
few special ones.

01:16:00.660 --> 01:16:05.810 align:middle line:84%
And this is a reasonable
model to picture in your mind.

01:16:05.810 --> 01:16:08.150 align:middle line:84%
That sphere is like
all of the projections

01:16:08.150 --> 01:16:11.060 align:middle line:84%
or all of the linear maps,
and that orange circle

01:16:11.060 --> 01:16:16.010 align:middle line:84%
is the ones that come up
in homogeneous dynamics.

01:16:16.010 --> 01:16:17.240 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:16:17.240 --> 01:16:17.970 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:16:17.970 --> 01:16:21.410 align:middle line:84%
So in the last two minutes,
I will write down a theorem

01:16:21.410 --> 01:16:22.180 align:middle line:90%
that they proved.

01:16:22.180 --> 01:16:43.670 align:middle line:90%


01:16:43.670 --> 01:16:46.520 align:middle line:90%
At least approximately.

01:16:46.520 --> 01:16:53.090 align:middle line:84%
OK, so this is Lindenstrauss,
Mohammadi, Wang, and Yang.

01:16:53.090 --> 01:16:56.100 align:middle line:90%
So setup is on that board.

01:16:56.100 --> 01:17:08.060 align:middle line:84%
So if G is SL 3, R, gamma
is SL 3, Z, U as above.

01:17:08.060 --> 01:17:08.760 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:08.760 --> 01:17:17.000 align:middle line:84%
We take X and we
suppose U dot X is not

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:21.523 align:middle line:84%
close to a proper
homogeneous subspace.

01:17:21.523 --> 01:17:26.210 align:middle line:90%


01:17:26.210 --> 01:17:30.070 align:middle line:84%
So this is some analog of
being not close to periodic.

01:17:30.070 --> 01:17:30.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:17:30.940 --> 01:17:39.340 align:middle line:84%
Then the conclusion
is that U 0, T of X

01:17:39.340 --> 01:17:47.420 align:middle line:84%
is delta dense in the
homogeneous space,

01:17:47.420 --> 01:17:49.553 align:middle line:84%
but so the homogeneous
space has infinite diameter,

01:17:49.553 --> 01:17:50.720 align:middle line:90%
so this can't quite be true.

01:17:50.720 --> 01:17:53.930 align:middle line:84%
But in the-- if you
cut off the cusp--

01:17:53.930 --> 01:17:58.840 align:middle line:84%
so you cut off the cusp, so you
have a compact piece of this.

01:17:58.840 --> 01:18:03.280 align:middle line:90%
And delta is T to the minus c.

01:18:03.280 --> 01:18:05.610 align:middle line:84%
c greater than 0 is
a universal constant.

01:18:05.610 --> 01:18:10.690 align:middle line:90%


01:18:10.690 --> 01:18:11.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:18:11.530 --> 01:18:14.920 align:middle line:84%
And a key step in
the proof is to first

01:18:14.920 --> 01:18:18.220 align:middle line:84%
show an estimate of the kind
that we were talking about,

01:18:18.220 --> 01:18:22.740 align:middle line:84%
that the delta-covering number
of this orbit is pretty big.

01:18:22.740 --> 01:18:28.450 align:middle line:90%


01:18:28.450 --> 01:18:31.210 align:middle line:84%
So the biggest it could possibly
be would be delta to the minus

01:18:31.210 --> 01:18:32.627 align:middle line:84%
the dimension of
the group, that's

01:18:32.627 --> 01:18:34.550 align:middle line:84%
the delta-covering number
of the whole space.

01:18:34.550 --> 01:18:36.770 align:middle line:90%
And it's quite close to that.

01:18:36.770 --> 01:18:37.910 align:middle line:90%
That's a key step.

01:18:37.910 --> 01:18:40.300 align:middle line:84%
It's an analogous to the
proof that we sketched

01:18:40.300 --> 01:18:43.210 align:middle line:90%
for the simpler SL 2, R case.

01:18:43.210 --> 01:18:45.140 align:middle line:84%
And there is an
additional argument,

01:18:45.140 --> 01:18:49.450 align:middle line:84%
but it seems like the most novel
and important part of this paper

01:18:49.450 --> 01:18:54.670 align:middle line:84%
was using projection theory,
using those kind of theorems,

01:18:54.670 --> 01:18:59.710 align:middle line:84%
plus some other smart stuff
to show that the orbit covers

01:18:59.710 --> 01:19:00.465 align:middle line:90%
a lot of ground.

01:19:00.465 --> 01:19:04.780 align:middle line:90%


01:19:04.780 --> 01:19:06.550 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:19:06.550 --> 01:19:09.208 align:middle line:84%
OK, so homogeneous
dynamics is a big subject,

01:19:09.208 --> 01:19:11.500 align:middle line:84%
and there are different
techniques, but in this course,

01:19:11.500 --> 01:19:13.930 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to show that there's
a connection to projection

01:19:13.930 --> 01:19:16.120 align:middle line:84%
theory, which is one
set of techniques,

01:19:16.120 --> 01:19:19.860 align:middle line:84%
and which helps to say
some interesting things.

01:19:19.860 --> 01:19:27.000 align:middle line:90%